 1,305\n|area_water_km2          = 3,379\n|area_water_percent      = 1.7\n|population_rank         = 46th\n|population_as_of        = 2019\n|2010Pop                 = 884,659\n|population_density_rank = 46th\n|2000DensityUS           = 11.44\n|2000Density             = 4.42\n|MedianHouseholdIncome   = $56,521<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kff.org/other/state-indicator/median-annual-income/?currentTimeframe=0|website=The Henry J. Kaiser Family Foundation|title=Median Annual Household Income|accessdate=December 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220091007/http://kff.org/other/state-indicator/median-annual-income/?currentTimeframe=0|archive-date=December 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|IncomeRank              = 30th\n|AdmittanceOrder         = 39th or 40th\n|AdmittanceDate          = November 2, 1889\n|timezone1               = [[Central Time Zone (North America)|Central]]\n|utc_offset1             = \u221206:00\n|timezone1_DST           = [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n|utc_offset1_DST         = \u221205:00\n|timezone1_location      = eastern half\n|timezone2               = [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain]]\n|utc_offset2             = \u221207:00\n|timezone2_DST           = [[Mountain Daylight Time|MDT]]\n|utc_offset2_DST         = \u221206:00\n|timezone2_location      = western half\n|Latitude                = 42\u00b029\u2032 N to 45\u00b056\u2032 N\n|Longitude               = 96\u00b026\u2032 W to 104\u00b003\u2032 W\n|width_mi                = 210\n|width_km                = 340\n|length_mi               = 380\n|length_km               = 610\n|elevation_max_point     = [[Black Elk Peak]]<ref>{{cite ngs|id=OT0810|designation=Black Elk Peak|accessdate=15 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=usgs>{{cite web|url=http://egsc.usgs.gov/isb//pubs/booklets/elvadist/elvadist.html|title=Elevations and Distances in the United States|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|year=2001|accessdate=January 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109183109/http://egsc.usgs.gov/isb//pubs/booklets/elvadist/elvadist.html|archive-date=November 9, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=NAVD88>Elevation adjusted to [[North American Vertical Datum of 1988]].</ref>\n|elevation_max_ft        = 7,244\n|elevation_max_m         = 2208\n|elevation_ft            = 2,200\n|elevation_m             = 670\n|elevation_min_point     = [[Big Stone Lake]] on {{nobreak|[[Minnesota]] border}}<ref name=usgs/><ref name=NAVD88/>\n|elevation_min_ft        = 968\n|elevation_min_m         = 295\n|iso_code                = US-SD\n|website                 = {{URL|www.sd.gov|SD.Gov}}\n}}\n{{Infobox U.S. state symbols\n|Name= South Dakota\n|Flag = Flag of South Dakota.svg\n|Seal = Seal of South Dakota.svg\n|Mammal = [[Coyote]]\n|Bird = [[Common pheasant|Ring-necked pheasant]]\n|Fish = [[Walleye]]\n|Flower = [[Pasque flower|American Pasque flower]]\n|Insect = [[Western honeybee]]\n|Tree = [[Spruce|Black Hills Spruce]]\n|Grass = [[Wheat grass|Western wheat grass]]\n|Beverage = [[Milk]]\n|Dance = [[Square dance]]\n|Fossil = [[Triceratops]]\n|Gemstone = [[Agate|Fairburn agate]]\n|Rock = [[Quartz|Rose quartz]]\n|Soil = [[Houdek (soil)|Houdek]]\n|Other = [[Kuchen]] (state dessert)\n|Route Marker = SD 20.svg\n|Quarter = 2006 SD Proof.png\n|QuarterReleaseDate = 2006\n}}\n\n'''South Dakota''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-us-South Dakota.ogg|-|_|d|\u0259|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|t|\u0259}}) is a [[U.S. state]] in the [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern region]] of the [[United States]]. It is named after the [[Lakota people|Lakota]] and Dakota [[Sioux]] [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] tribes, who compose a large portion of the population and historically dominated the territory. South Dakota is the [[List of U.S. states and territories by area|seventeenth largest by area]], but the [[List of U.S. states and territories by population|fifth smallest by population]] and the [[List of U.S. states and territories by population density|5th least densely populated]] of the [[List of U.S. states|50 United States]]. As the southern part of the former [[Dakota Territory]], South Dakota became a state on November 2, 1889, simultaneously with [[North Dakota]]. [[Pierre, South Dakota|Pierre]] is the state capital and [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]], with a population of about 187,200,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siouxfalls.org/news/2019/February/04/population|title=Sioux Falls Population Grows to Estimated 187,200|publisher=City of Sioux Falls|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref> is South Dakota's largest city.\n\nSouth Dakota is bordered by the states of [[North Dakota]] (to the north), [[Minnesota]] (to the east), [[Iowa]] (to the southeast), [[Nebraska]] (to the south), [[Wyoming]] (to the west), and [[Montana]] (to the northwest). The state is bisected by the [[Missouri River]], dividing South Dakota into two geographically and socially distinct halves, known to residents as \"[[East River (South Dakota)|East River]]\" and \"[[West River (South Dakota)|West River]]\".<ref name=eastwestriver>Hasselstrom, pp. 2\u20134.</ref>\n\nEastern South Dakota is home to most of the state's population, and the area's fertile soil is used to grow a variety of crops. West of the Missouri River, [[ranch]]ing is the predominant agricultural activity, and the economy is more dependent on tourism and defense spending. Most of the Native American reservations are in [[West River (South Dakota)|West River]]. The [[Black Hills]], a group of low pine-covered mountains sacred to the Sioux, are in the southwest part of the state. [[Mount Rushmore]], a major tourist destination, is there. South Dakota has a temperate [[continental climate]], with four distinct seasons and precipitation ranging from moderate in the east to semi-arid in the west. The state's ecology features species typical of a North American [[grassland]] biome.\n\nHumans have inhabited the area for several millennia, with the Sioux becoming dominant by the early 19th century. In the late 19th century, European-American settlement intensified after a [[Black Hills Gold Rush|gold rush]] in the Black Hills and the construction of railroads from the east. Encroaching miners and settlers triggered a number of [[American Indian Wars|Indian wars]], ending with the [[Wounded Knee Massacre]] in 1890. Key events in the 20th century included the [[Dust Bowl]] and [[Great Depression]], increased federal spending during the 1940s and 1950s for agriculture and defense, and an industrialization of agriculture that has reduced family farming.\n\nWhile several [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] have represented South Dakota for multiple terms in both chambers of [[Congress (United States)|Congress]], the state government is largely controlled by the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], whose nominees have carried South Dakota in each of the last 13 [[United States presidential election|presidential elections]]. Historically dominated by an agricultural economy and a rural lifestyle, South Dakota has recently sought to diversify its economy in areas to attract and retain residents. South Dakota's history and rural character still strongly influence the state's culture.\n\n==Geography==\n\n{{Main|Geography of South Dakota}}\n[[File:South Dakota general map 2.png|thumb|left|upright=1.15|Terrain and primary geographic features of South Dakota]]\n\nSouth Dakota is in the north-central United States, and is considered a part of the [[Midwest]] by the U.S. Census Bureau;<ref>[http://www2.census.gov/geo/pdfs/maps-data/maps/reference/us_regdiv.pdf Census Regions and Divisions of the United States] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171219134403/https://www2.census.gov/geo/pdfs/maps-data/maps/reference/us_regdiv.pdf |date=December 19, 2017 }}, U.S. Census Bureau. Retrieved January 19, 2016.</ref> it is also part of the [[Great Plains]] region. The culture, economy, and geography of western South Dakota have more in common with the [[Western United States|West]] than the Midwest.<ref name=eastwestriver/><ref name=NYTimesEastWest>Johnson, Dirk. ''Gold Divides Dakotans as River Did'' [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE1DF1539F93AA35753C1A96E948260 NYtimes.com] ''[[The New York Times]]''. October 9, 1988. (accessed February 14, 2008)</ref> South Dakota has a total area of {{convert|77116|sqmi|km2}}, making the state the [[List of U.S. states by area|17th largest]] in the Union.<ref name=SDArea>{{cite web| url =https://www.census.gov/geo/reference/state-area.html| title =State Area Measurements (2010)| publisher =U.S. Census| accessdate =March 26, 2015| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20180316004512/https://www.census.gov/geo/reference/state-area.html| archive-date =March 16, 2018| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Black Elk Peak]], formerly named Harney Peak, with an elevation of {{convert|7242|ft|m|abbr=on}}, is the state's highest point, while the shoreline of [[Big Stone Lake]] is the lowest, with an elevation of {{convert|966|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=usgs/> South Dakota is bordered to the north by [[North Dakota]]; to the south by [[Nebraska]]; to the east by [[Iowa]] and [[Minnesota]]; and to the west by [[Wyoming]] and [[Montana]]. The geographical center of the U.S. is {{convert|17|mi|km}} west of Castle Rock in [[Butte County, South Dakota|Butte County]].<ref name=usgs/> The North American continental [[pole of inaccessibility]] is between [[Allen, South Dakota|Allen]] and [[Kyle, South Dakota|Kyle]], {{convert|1024|mi|km|abbr=on}} from the nearest coastline.<ref name=\"PIA\">{{Cite journal |doi=10.1080/14702540801897809 |volume=123 |issue=3 |pages=227\u2013233 |last=Garcia-Castellanos |first=D. |author2=U. Lombardo |title=Poles of Inaccessibility: A Calculation Algorithm for the Remotest Places on Earth |journal=Scottish Geographical Journal |year=2007 |url=http://cuba.ija.csic.es/~danielgc/papers/Garcia-Castellanos,%20Lombardo,%202007,%20SGJ.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629230429/http://cuba.ija.csic.es/~danielgc/papers/Garcia-Castellanos,%20Lombardo,%202007,%20SGJ.pdf |archivedate=June 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Missouri River]] is the largest and longest river in the United States. Other major South Dakota rivers include the [[Cheyenne River|Cheyenne]], [[James River (Dakotas)|James]], [[Big Sioux River|Big Sioux]], and [[White River (Missouri River)|White]] Rivers. Eastern South Dakota has many natural lakes, mostly created by periods of glaciation.<ref name=Thompson1718>Thompson (ed.), pp. 17\u201318.</ref> Additionally, dams on the Missouri River create four large reservoirs: [[Oahe Dam|Lake Oahe]], [[Lake Sharpe]], [[Lake Francis Case]], and [[Lewis and Clark Lake]].\n\n===Regions and geology===\n\nSouth Dakota can generally be divided into three regions: eastern South Dakota, western South Dakota, and the [[Black Hills]].<ref>Thompson (ed.), p. 14.</ref> The Missouri River serves as a boundary in terms of geographic, social, and political differences between eastern and western South Dakota. The geography of the Black Hills, long considered sacred by Native Americans, differs from its surroundings to such an extent it can be considered separate from the rest of western South Dakota. At times the Black Hills are combined with the rest of western South Dakota, and people often refer to the resulting two regions divided by the Missouri River as [[West River (South Dakota)|West River]] and [[East River (South Dakota)|East River]].<ref name=eastwestriver/><ref name=NYTimesEastWest/>\n[[File:Badlands panorama1.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.15|[[Badlands National Park]]]]\n\nEastern South Dakota generally features higher precipitation and lower topography than the western part of the state. Smaller geographic regions of this area include the [[Coteau des Prairies]], the [[Dissected Till Plains]], and the James River Valley. The Coteau des Prairies is a plateau bordered on the east by the [[Minnesota River]] Valley and on the west by the James River Basin.<ref name=Thompson1718/> Further west, the James River Basin is mostly low, flat, highly eroded land, following the flow of the [[James River (Dakotas)|James River]] through South Dakota from north to south.<ref>Schell, pp. 4\u20136.</ref> The Dissected Till Plains, an area of rolling hills and fertile soil that covers much of Iowa and Nebraska, extends into the southeastern corner of South Dakota. Layers deposited during the [[Pleistocene]] epoch, starting around two million years ago, cover most of eastern South Dakota.<ref name=NSUgeology/> These are the youngest rock and sediment layers in the state, the product of several successive periods of [[glacier|glaciation]] which deposited a large amount of rocks and soil, known as [[till]], over the area.<ref name=pleistocene>{{cite web| title = Pleistocene Deposits | publisher=South Dakota Department of Environment & Natural Resources | accessdate =November 28, 2008 | url = http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/pleistocene.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080116121210/http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/pleistocene.html | archivedate = January 16, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Great Plains]] cover most of the western two-thirds of South Dakota. West of the [[Missouri River]] the landscape becomes more arid and rugged, consisting of rolling hills, plains, ravines, and steep flat-topped hills called [[butte]]s.<ref>Schell, p. 6.</ref> In the south, east of the Black Hills, lie the South Dakota [[Badlands National Park|Badlands]]. Erosion from the Black Hills, marine skeletons which fell to the bottom of a large shallow sea that once covered the area, and volcanic material all contribute to the geology of this area.<ref name=NSUgeology/><ref name=mesozoic>{{cite web| title = Mesozoic Formations | publisher=South Dakota Department of Environment & Natural Resources | accessdate =November 28, 2008 | url = http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/mesozoic.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080213170116/http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/mesozoic.html | archivedate = February 13, 2008}}</ref><ref name=tertiary>{{cite web| title = Tertiary Formations | publisher=South Dakota Department of Environment & Natural Resources | accessdate =November 28, 2008 | url = http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/tertiary.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070925065217/http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/tertiary.html | archivedate = September 25, 2007}}</ref>\n[[File:Harney Peak 4.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.15|The [[Black Hills]], a low mountain range, is located in Southwestern South Dakota.]]\n\nThe Black Hills are in the southwestern part of South Dakota and extend into [[Wyoming]]. This range of low mountains covers {{convert|6000|sqmi|km2|abbr=on}}, with peaks that rise from 2,000 to 4,000 feet (600 to 1,200&nbsp;m) above their bases. The Black Hills are the location of [[Black Elk Peak]] (7,242 ft or 2,207 m above sea level), the highest point in South Dakota and also the highest point in the United States east of the [[Rocky Mountains]].<ref name=usgs/> Two billion-year-old [[Precambrian]] formations, the oldest rocks in the state, form the central core of the Black Hills.<ref name=NSUgeology>{{cite web | title = The Geology of South Dakota | publisher = Northern State University | accessdate = August 29, 2008 | url = http://www3.northern.edu/natsource/EARTH/Geolog1.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081001125824/http://www.northern.edu/natsource/EARTH/Geolog1.htm | archive-date = October 1, 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=Precambrian>{{cite web| title = Precambrian Formations | publisher=South Dakota Department of Environment & Natural Resources | accessdate =November 28, 2008 | url = http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/precambrian.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080116121220/http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/precambrian.html | archivedate = January 16, 2008}}</ref> Formations from the [[Paleozoic Era]] form the outer ring of the Black Hills;<ref name=paleozoic>{{cite web| title = Paleozoic Formations | publisher=South Dakota Department of Environment & Natural Resources | accessdate =November 28, 2008 | url = http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/paleozoic.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080116121205/http://www.sdgs.usd.edu/geology/paleozoic.html | archivedate = January 16, 2008}}</ref> these were created between roughly 540 and 250 million years ago. This area features rocks such as [[limestone]], which were deposited here when the area formed the shoreline of an ancient inland sea.<ref name=paleozoic/>\n\n===Ecology===\n\n[[File:Thunder butte SD.jpg|thumb|Much of western South Dakota is covered by [[Thunder Butte|butte]]s.]]\n\nMuch of South Dakota (except for the Black Hills area) is dominated by a temperate [[grassland]] [[biome]].<ref>{{cite web| title = A Short Introduction to Terrestrial Biomes | publisher=nearctica.com | accessdate =September 22, 2007 | url = http://www.nearctica.com/ecology/habitats/biointro.htm | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020341/http://www.nearctica.com/ecology/habitats/biointro.htm<!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate =September 28, 2007}}</ref> Although grasses and crops cover most of this region, [[deciduous]] trees such as [[Populus sect. Aegiros|cottonwoods]], elms, and [[willow]]s are common near rivers and in [[shelter belt]]s.<ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota Flora | publisher = Northern State University | accessdate = September 22, 2007 | url = http://www3.northern.edu/natsource/flora1.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071001164057/http://www.northern.edu/natsource/flora1.htm | archive-date = October 1, 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n[[Mammals]] in this area include [[American bison|bison]], [[deer]], [[pronghorn]], [[coyotes]], and [[prairie dog]]s.<ref name=SDFauna>{{cite web | title = South Dakota Fauna | publisher = Northern State University | accessdate = September 22, 2007 | url = http://www3.northern.edu/natsource/fauna1.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071015051320/http://northern.edu/natsource/fauna1.htm | archive-date = October 15, 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The state bird, the [[common pheasant|ring-necked pheasant]], has adapted well to the area after being introduced from [[China]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Ring-Necked Pheasant | publisher = Northern State University | accessdate = September 22, 2007 | url = http://www3.northern.edu/natsource/BIRDS/Ringne1.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071015051301/http://northern.edu/natsource/BIRDS/Ringne1.htm | archive-date = October 15, 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Growing populations of [[bald eagle]]s are spread throughout the state, especially near the [[Missouri River]].<ref>Hetland, Cara. \"South Dakota bald eagles make a comeback\" [http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2007/02/07/sdeaglesuccess/ Publicradio.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015051544/http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2007/02/07/sdeaglesuccess/ |date=October 15, 2007 }} [[Minnesota Public Radio]]. February 8, 2007. (accessed September 22, 2007).</ref> Rivers and lakes of the grasslands support populations of [[walleye]], [[carp]], [[Pike (fish)|pike]], [[bass (fish)|bass]], and other species.<ref name=SDFauna/> The Missouri River also contains the pre-historic [[American paddlefish|paddlefish]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Paddlefish | publisher = Northern State University | accessdate = September 22, 2007 | url = http://www3.northern.edu/natsource/ENDANG1/Paddle1.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071015051309/http://northern.edu/natsource/ENDANG1/Paddle1.htm | archive-date = October 15, 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nDue to a higher elevation and level of precipitation, the Black Hills ecology differs significantly from the plains.<ref>[http://nrs.fs.fed.us/pubs/rb/rb_nrs005.pdf \"South Dakota's Forest Resources\". Piva, R.; Haugan, D.; Josten, G.; Brand, G.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312234431/http://www.nrs.fs.fed.us/pubs/rb/rb_nrs005.pdf |date=March 12, 2009 }} (U.S. Department of Interior. ''Forest Service Resource Bulletin''. 2007)</ref> The mountains are thickly blanketed by various types of [[pine]]s, including [[Ponderosa pine|ponderosa]] and [[Pinus contorta|lodgepole pines]], as well as [[spruces]].<ref name=Thompson31>Thompson (ed.), p. 31.</ref> Black Hills mammals include [[deer]], [[elk|elk (wapiti)]], [[bighorn sheep]], [[mountain goat]]s, [[American marten|pine marten]], and [[mountain lion]]s, while the streams and lakes contain several species of [[trout]].<ref name=Thompson31/><ref>{{cite web | title = Deer | publisher = [[South Dakota Department of Game, Fish and Parks]] | accessdate = January 23, 2016 | url = http://gfp.sd.gov/hunting/big-game/deer/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160130014243/http://gfp.sd.gov/hunting/big-game/deer/ | archive-date = January 30, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Fishing | publisher = [[Black Hills National Forest]] | accessdate = January 27, 2016 | url = http://www.fs.usda.gov/activity/blackhills/recreation/fishing | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160204072932/http://www.fs.usda.gov/activity/blackhills/recreation/fishing | archive-date = February 4, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n\n[[File:South Dakota K\u00f6ppen.svg|thumb|K\u00f6ppen climate types in South Dakota]]\n\nSouth Dakota has a [[continental climate]] with four distinct seasons, ranging from cold, dry winters to hot and semi-humid summers. During the summers, the state's average high temperature is often close to {{convert|90|\u00b0F}}, although it cools to near {{convert|60|\u00b0F}} at night. It is not unusual for South Dakota to have severe hot, dry spells in the summer with the temperature climbing above {{convert|100|\u00b0F}} several times a year.<ref name=SDclimate>{{cite web|url=http://www5.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim60/states/Clim_SD_01.pdf |title=Climate of South Dakota |publisher=National Climatic Data Center |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624205247/http://www5.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim60/states/Clim_SD_01.pdf |archivedate=June 24, 2008 }}</ref> Winters are cold with January high temperatures averaging below freezing and low temperatures averaging below {{convert|10|\u00b0F}} in most of the state. The highest recorded temperature is {{convert|120|F|C}} at [[Usta, South Dakota|Usta]] on July 15, 2006<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.usatoday.com/weather/wheat7.htm | title = Each state's high temperature record | newspaper = [[USA Today]] | accessdate = March 1, 2012 | date = November 1, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120703051245/http://www.usatoday.com/weather/wheat7.htm | archive-date = July 3, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> and the lowest recorded temperature is {{convert|-58|F|C}} at [[McIntosh, South Dakota|McIntosh]] on February 17, 1936.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.usatoday.com/weather/wcstates.htm | title = Each state's low temperature record | newspaper = [[USA Today]] | accessdate = March 1, 2012 | date = February 10, 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120827011331/http://www.usatoday.com/weather/wcstates.htm | archive-date = August 27, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nAverage annual [[precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]] in South Dakota ranges from [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] conditions in the northwestern part of the state (around {{convert|15|in|disp=or|abbr=out}}) to semi-humid around the southeast portion of the state (around {{convert|25|in|disp=or|abbr=out}}),<ref name=SDclimate/> although a small area centered on [[Lead, South Dakota|Lead]] in the [[Black Hills]] has the highest precipitation at nearly {{convert|30|in}} per year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Precipitation Normals (1971\u20132000) |publisher=South Dakota State University |accessdate=November 26, 2008 |url=http://climate.sdstate.edu/archives/data/pptnormals.shtm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120417160056/http://climate.sdstate.edu/archives/data/pptnormals.shtm |archivedate=April 17, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSouth Dakota summers bring frequent, sometimes severe, thunderstorms with high winds, thunder, and hail. The state's eastern part is often considered part of [[Tornado Alley]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Tornado Alley | publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] | accessdate = January 27, 2016 | url = https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/climate-information/extreme-events/us-tornado-climatology/tornado-alley | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181113213336/https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/climate-information/extreme-events/us-tornado-climatology/tornado-alley | archive-date = November 13, 2018 | url-status = live }}</ref> and South Dakota experiences an average of 30 tornadoes each year.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/img/climate/research/tornado/small/avgt5304.gif | title = Annual Average Number of Tornadoes, 1953\u20132004 | publisher = National Climatic Data Center | accessdate = June 25, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111016174155/http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/img/climate/research/tornado/small/avgt5304.gif | archive-date = October 16, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref> Severe [[blizzard]]s and [[ice storm]]s occur often during winter.\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 90%;\" |\n|+ '''Monthly average high and low temperatures for various South Dakota Cities, in [[Fahrenheit]] degrees'''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | City\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Jan\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Feb\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Mar\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Apr\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | May\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Jun\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Jul\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Aug\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Sep\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Oct\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Nov\n! style=\"background:#e5afaa;\" | Dec\n|-\n! <br /> !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" | !! data-sort-type=\"number\" |\n|- style=\"background:#f8f3ca;\"\n! style=\"background:#f8f3ca;\" | [[Aberdeen, South Dakota|Aberdeen]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Monthly Averages for Aberdeen, SD | publisher = weather.com | accessdate = 2008-08-08 | url = http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0001?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120309155023/http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0001?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-date = March 9, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n| 21/1\n| 29/9\n| 40/21\n| 57/33\n| 70/46\n| 79/55\n| 85/60\n| 84/57\n| 73/47\n| 59/34\n| 39/20\n| 26/6\n|- style=\"background:#c5dfe1;\"\n! style=\"background:#c5dfe1;\" | [[Huron, South Dakota|Huron]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Monthly Averages for Huron, SD | publisher = weather.com | accessdate = August 8, 2008 | url = http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0164?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110522133204/http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0164?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-date = May 22, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n| 25/4\n| 31/11\n| 43/22\n| 58/34\n| 70/46\n| 80/55\n| 86/61\n| 84/59\n| 75/47\n| 61/35\n| 41/21\n| 29/8\n|- style=\"background:#f8f3ca;\"\n! style=\"background:#f8f3ca;\" | [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Monthly Averages for Rapid City, SD | publisher = weather.com | accessdate = August 8, 2008 | url = http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0283?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080407060414/http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0283?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-date = April 7, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n| 34/10\n| 38/14\n| 45/21\n| 55/31\n| 65/42\n| 75/52\n| 83/58\n| 82/55\n| 73/45\n| 61/34\n| 44/21\n| 37/13\n|- style=\"background:#c5dfe1;\"\n! style=\"background:#c5dfe1;\" | [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Monthly Averages for Sioux Falls, SD | publisher = weather.com | accessdate = August 8, 2008 | url = http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0315?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110522133239/http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USSD0315?from=36hr_bottomnav_undeclared | archive-date = May 22, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n| 25/3\n| 32/10\n| 44/21\n| 59/33\n| 71/45\n| 81/55\n| 86/60\n| 83/58\n| 74/48\n| 61/35\n| 42/21\n| 29/8\n|}\n\n===National parks and monuments===\n\n[[File:20100324-F-LSC-140 (33845911384).jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|[[Mount Rushmore]] in the Black Hills]]\n\nSouth Dakota has several sites administered by the [[National Park Service]]. Two [[national parks]] have been established in South Dakota, both in the state's southwestern part. [[Wind Cave National Park]], established in 1903 in the [[Black Hills]], has an extensive cave network as well as a large herd of [[American Bison|bison]].<ref>Nettinga, Curt. ''Saving the bison may have saved Wind Cave Park''. [http://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/communities/hot-springs/community/saving-the-bison-may-have-saved-wind-cave-park/article_5cdb8bda-0365-11e3-9a3e-001a4bcf887a.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917111016/http://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/communities/hot-springs/community/saving-the-bison-may-have-saved-wind-cave-park/article_5cdb8bda-0365-11e3-9a3e-001a4bcf887a.html |date=September 17, 2013 }} ''[[Rapid City Journal]]''. August 13, 2013. (accessed January 29, 2016)</ref> [[Badlands National Park]] was created in 1978.<ref>{{cite web | title = Frequently Asked Questions (Badlands National Park) | publisher = National Park Service | accessdate = August 27, 2007 | url = http://www.nps.gov/badl/faqs.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070822005642/http://www.nps.gov/badl/faqs.htm | archive-date = August 22, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> The park features an eroded, brightly colored landscape surrounded by [[semi-arid]] grasslands.<ref>{{cite web | title = Badlands | publisher = National Park Service | accessdate = August 27, 2007 | url = http://www.nps.gov/badl | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070824080349/http://www.nps.gov/badl | archive-date = August 24, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> [[Mount Rushmore]] National Memorial in the Black Hills was established in 1925. The sculpture of four U.S. Presidents was carved into the mountainside by sculptor [[Gutzon Borglum]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Student Guide | publisher = National Park Service | accessdate = January 29, 2016 | url = http://www.nps.gov/moru/learn/kidsyouth/upload/MORU-Student-Guide-2014.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150911181239/http://www.nps.gov/moru/learn/kidsyouth/upload/MORU-Student-Guide-2014.pdf | archive-date = September 11, 2015 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nOther areas managed by the National Park Service include [[Jewel Cave National Monument]] near [[Custer, South Dakota|Custer]], the [[Lewis and Clark National Historic Trail]], the [[Minuteman Missile National Historic Site]], which features a decommissioned [[nuclear missile silo]] and a separate missile control area several miles away, and the [[Missouri National Recreational River]].<ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota | publisher = National Park Service | accessdate = August 28, 2007 | url = http://www.nps.gov/state/SD/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071001145001/http://www.nps.gov/state/sd/ | archive-date = October 1, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> The [[Crazy Horse Memorial]] is a large mountainside sculpture near Mt. Rushmore being built with private funds.<ref>Hetland, Cara. ''Crazy Horse Memorial turns 60 this year'' [http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2008/06/02/crazyhorse60 Publicradio.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130083252/http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2008/06/02/crazyhorse60 |date=January 30, 2009 }} [[Minnesota Public Radio]]. June 8, 2008. (accessed February 7, 2009).</ref> The [[Mammoth Site, Hot Springs|Mammoth Site]] near [[Hot Springs, South Dakota|Hot Springs]] is another privately owned attraction in the Black Hills. A working paleontological dig, the site has one of the world's largest concentrations of mammoth remains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mammothsite.com|title=Home|website=Mammoth Site of Hot Springs|access-date=December 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809223106/http://mammothsite.com/|archive-date=August 9, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n<!--This section is linked from [[List of capitals in the United States]]-->\n{{Main|History of South Dakota}}\n{{See also|Timeline of South Dakota}}\n\nHumans have lived in what is today South Dakota for several thousand years. The first inhabitants were [[Paleoindian]] [[hunter-gatherer]]s, and disappeared from the area around 5000 BC.<ref>Schell, p. 15.</ref> Between 500&nbsp;AD and 800&nbsp;AD, a semi-nomadic people known as the Mound Builders lived in central and eastern South Dakota. In the 14th century, the [[Crow Creek Massacre]] occurred, in which several hundred men, women, and children were killed near the [[Missouri River]].<ref name=DeloriaNeal>Deloria and Neal (eds.), p. 161.</ref>\n\nBy 1500, the [[Arikara]] (or Ree) had settled in much of the Missouri River valley.<ref>Schell, pp. 16\u201318.</ref> European contact with the area began in 1743, when the [[Louis-Joseph Gaultier de La V\u00e9rendrye|LaV\u00e9rendrye]] brothers explored the region. The LaV\u00e9rendrye group buried a plate near the site of modern-day [[Pierre, South Dakota|Pierre]], claiming the region for France as part of [[Louisiana (New France)|greater Louisiana]].<ref>Schell, pp. 28\u201329.</ref> In 1762 the entire region became part of the [[Louisiana (New Spain)|Spanish Louisiana]] until 1802.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/349302/Louisiana-Purchase|title=Louisiana Purchase\u2014History, Facts, & Map|publisher=|access-date=December 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501010249/http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/349302/Louisiana-Purchase|archive-date=May 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowla.org/entry/773/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403103905/http://www.knowla.org/entry/773/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2014-04-03|title=Spanish Colonial Louisiana\u2014Know Louisiana}}</ref> By the early 19th century, the [[Sioux]] had largely replaced the Arikara as the dominant group in the area.<ref>Schell, pp. 18\u201321.</ref>\n\nIn 1803, the United States purchased the [[Louisiana Territory]], an area that included most of South Dakota, from [[Napoleon Bonaparte]], and President [[Thomas Jefferson]] organized a group commonly referred to as the \"[[Lewis and Clark Expedition]]\" to explore the region.<ref>Thompson (ed.), pp. 56\u201357.</ref> In 1817, an American fur trading post was set up at present-day [[Fort Pierre, South Dakota|Fort Pierre]], beginning continuous American settlement of the area.<ref name=SDChrono>{{cite web| title = Chronology of South Dakota History | publisher=South Dakota Historical Society | accessdate =September 3, 2007 | url = http://www.sdhistory.org/soc/soc_hist.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070901170704/http://www.sdhistory.org/soc/soc_hist.htm |archivedate = September 1, 2007}}</ref> In 1855, the U.S. Army bought [[Fort Pierre, South Dakota|Fort Pierre]] but abandoned it in 1857 in favor of [[Fort Randall]] to the south.<ref name=SDChrono/> Settlement by Americans and Europeans was by this time increasing rapidly, and in 1858 the [[Yankton Sioux]] signed the [[List of United States treaties|1858 Treaty]], ceding most of present-day eastern South Dakota to the United States.<ref>Thompson (ed.), pp. 69\u201371.</ref>\n[[File:Deadwood13.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.9|[[Deadwood, South Dakota|Deadwood]], like many other [[Black Hills]] towns, was founded after the discovery of gold.]]\n\nLand speculators founded two of eastern South Dakota's largest present-day cities: [[Sioux Falls]] in 1856<ref>Schell, pp. 72\u201373.</ref> and [[Yankton, South Dakota|Yankton]] in 1859.<ref>Schell, p. 72.</ref> In 1861, the [[Dakota Territory]] was established by the United States government (this initially included [[North Dakota]], South Dakota, and parts of [[Montana]] and [[Wyoming]]).<ref>{{cite web | title = Dakota Territory | publisher = State Historical Society of North Dakota | accessdate = January 30, 2016 | url = http://history.nd.gov/archives/stateagencies/dtrecords.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160216061723/http://history.nd.gov/archives/stateagencies/dtrecords.html | archive-date = February 16, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> Settlement of the area, mostly by people from the eastern United States as well as western and northern [[Europe]], increased rapidly,<ref>Schell, pp 168\u2013170.</ref> especially after the completion of an eastern railway link to Yankton in 1873.<ref>Schell, p. 113.</ref>\n\nIn 1874, gold was discovered in the [[Black Hills]] during a military expedition led by [[George A. Custer]]<ref>Schell, p. 129.</ref><ref>Schell, pp. 140\u2013144.</ref> and miners and explorers began illegally entering land promised to the Lakota. Custer's expedition took place despite the fact that the [[Sioux]] had been granted the entire western half of present-day South Dakota ([[West River (South Dakota)|West River]]) in 1868 by the [[Treaty of Fort Laramie (1868)|Treaty of Laramie]] as part of the [[Great Sioux Reservation]].<ref>Thompson (ed.), p. 90.</ref> The Sioux declined to grant mining rights or land in the Black Hills, and war broke out after the U.S. failed to stop white miners and settlers from entering the region.<ref>Schell, p. 129; pp. 133\u201339.</ref> Eventually the U.S. won and broke up the Great Sioux Reservation into five reservations, settling the [[Lakota people|Lakota]] there.<ref name=SDChrono/> In 1980 the [[United States Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] and Congress ordered [[Black Hills Land Claim|compensation]] but the Lakota still refuse to [[Acceptance|accept]] it, insisting on return of their land.<ref>Thompson (ed.), p. 529.</ref>\n[[File:South Dakota harvest field-LCCN2008678244.tif|thumb|upright=1.15|A harvest in South Dakota, 1898]]\n\nA growing population and political concerns (admitting two states meant having four new senators for the Republican Party) caused Dakota Territory to be divided in half and President [[Benjamin Harrison]] signed proclamations formally admitting South Dakota and North Dakota to the union on November 2, 1889.<ref>Schell, p. 222.</ref><ref name=Thompson116>Thompson (ed.), pp. 115\u2013116.</ref> Harrison had the papers shuffled to obscure which one was signed first and the order went unrecorded.<ref name=Thompson116/><ref name=richardson>{{cite book|author=Heather Cox Richardson|date=25 November 2013|title=Wounded Knee: Party Politics and the Road to an American Massacre|publisher=Basic Books|page=101|quote=\"On February 22, 1889, outgoing President Cleveland signed an omnibus bill that divided the Territory of Dakota in half. The bill also enable the people in the new Territories of North Dakota and South Dakota, as well as the older territories of Montana and Washington, to write state constitutions and elect state governments. The four new states would be admitted into the Union in nine months. This plan cut Democratic New Mexico out of statehood, and split Republican Dakota Territory into two new Republican states. Rather than two new Republican states and two new Democratic states that Congress had considered the previous year, the omnibus bill created three new Republican states and one new Democratic state that Republicans thought they would capture. In their eagerness to admit both Dakotas, Republican congressmen also ignored the uncomfortable fact that much of the land in the anticipated state of South Dakota belonged to the Sioux|isbn=9780465025114|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Wounded_Knee.html?id=-Zi4H7SsSugC}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, 1890, the [[Wounded Knee Massacre]] occurred on the [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]]. Commonly cited as the last major armed conflict between the United States and the [[Lakota Sioux|Lakota Sioux Nation]], the massacre resulted in the deaths of at least 146 Sioux, many of them women and children.<ref name=Schell304>Schell, pp. 304\u2013305.</ref> 31 U.S. soldiers were also killed in the conflict.<ref name=Schell304/>\n[[File:Dust Bowl - Dallas, South Dakota 1936.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|A South Dakota farm during the [[Dust Bowl]], 1936]]\n\nDuring the 1930s, several economic and climatic conditions combined with disastrous results for South Dakota. A lack of rainfall, extremely high temperatures and inappropriate cultivation techniques produced what was known as the [[Dust Bowl]] in South Dakota and several other plains states. Fertile [[topsoil]] was blown away in massive dust storms, and several harvests were completely ruined.<ref>{{cite web| title = Drought in the Dust Bowl Years | publisher=National Drought Mitigation Center | accessdate =April 4, 2007 | url = http://drought.unl.edu/whatis/dustbowl.htm | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070329183000/http://www.drought.unl.edu/whatis/dustbowl.htm<!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate =March 29, 2007}}</ref> The experiences of the Dust Bowl, coupled with local bank [[foreclosure]]s and the general economic effects of the [[Great Depression]], resulted in many South Dakotans leaving the state. The population of South Dakota declined by more than 7% between 1930 and 1940.<ref>{{cite web | title = Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990 | publisher = United States Census Bureau | accessdate = December 14, 2008 | url = https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/sd190090.txt | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081228081313/http://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/sd190090.txt | archive-date = December 28, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nEconomic stability returned with the U.S. entry into [[World War II]] in 1941, when demand for the state's agricultural and industrial products grew as the nation mobilized for war.<ref>Schell, pp. 317\u2013320.</ref> In 1944, the [[Pick\u2013Sloan Plan]] was passed as part of the [[Flood Control Act of 1944]] by the U.S. Congress, resulting in the construction of six large dams on the Missouri River, four of which are at least partially in South Dakota.<ref name=Schell323>Schell, pp. 323\u2013325.</ref> Flood control, [[hydroelectricity]], and recreational opportunities such as boating and fishing are provided by the dams and their reservoirs.<ref name=Schell323/>\n\nIn recent decades, South Dakota has been transformed from a state dominated by agriculture to one with a more diversified economy. The tourism industry has grown considerably since the completion of the interstate system in the 1960s, with the [[Black Hills]] becoming more important as a destination. The financial service industry began to grow in the state as well, with [[Citibank]] moving its credit card operations from [[New York (state)|New York]] to [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]] in 1981, a move that has been followed by several other financial companies. South Dakota was the first state to eliminate [[Usury#Usury statutes in the United States|caps on interest rates]].<ref name=Citibank>Hetland, Cara. ''Sioux Falls 25 years after Citibank's arrival''. [http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2006/02/23/siouxfalls Publicradio.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222075941/http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2006/02/23/siouxfalls |date=February 22, 2011 }} [[Minnesota Public Radio]]. February 24, 2006. (accessed March 23, 2007)</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the site of the recently closed [[Homestake Mine (South Dakota)|Homestake gold mine]] near [[Lead, South Dakota|Lead]] was chosen as the location of a new underground research facility, the [[Deep Underground Science and Engineering Laboratory]].<ref>{{cite web| title = Homestake Strikes Gold Again | publisher=South Dakota Science and Technology Authority | accessdate =August 28, 2007 | url = http://www.sanfordlaboratoryathomestake.org/news_07-10-07a.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071215142331/http://www.sanfordlaboratoryathomestake.org/news_07-10-07a.html | archivedate = December 15, 2007}}</ref> Despite a growing state population and recent economic development, many rural areas have been struggling over the past 50 years with locally declining populations and the emigration of educated young adults to larger South Dakota cities, such as [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]] or Sioux Falls, or to other states.<ref>{{cite web| title = Sweeping out the Plains | publisher=aliciapatterson.org | accessdate =April 5, 2007 | url = http://www.aliciapatterson.org/APF2102/Coffman_Anthan/Coffman_Anthan.html | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070403202243/http://aliciapatterson.org/APF2102/Coffman_Anthan/Coffman_Anthan.html<!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate =April 3, 2007}}</ref> Mechanization and consolidation of agriculture has contributed greatly to the declining number of smaller family farms and the resulting economic and demographic challenges facing rural towns.<ref>Thompson (ed.), pp. 542\u2013549.</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{Main|Demographics of South Dakota}}\n[[File:South Dakota population map.png|thumb|upright=1.6|South Dakota population density map]]\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 4837\n|1870= 11776\n|1880= 98268\n|1890= 348600\n|1900= 401570\n|1910= 583888\n|1920= 636547\n|1930= 692849\n|1940= 642961\n|1950= 652740\n|1960= 680514\n|1970= 665507\n|1980= 690768\n|1990= 696004\n|2000= 754844\n|2010= 814180\n|estimate= 884659\n|estyear= 2019\n|footnote=Source: 1910\u20132010<ref>{{cite web|author=Resident Population Data|url=http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php|title=Resident Population Data\u20142010 Census|publisher=2010.census.gov|accessdate=December 24, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101090833/http://2010.census.gov/2010census/data/apportionment-pop-text.php|archivedate=January 1, 2011}}</ref><br />2019 Estimate<ref name=\"PopEstUS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/SD,US/PST045219|title=QuickFacts South Dakota; UNITED STATES|format=|website=2018 Population Estimates|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827215414/https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/SD,US/PST045219|archive-date=August 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Population===\n\nThe [[United States Census Bureau]] estimates the population of South Dakota was 884,659 on July 1, 2019, an 8.66% increase since the [[2010 United States Census]], only [[North Dakota]], [[Alaska]], [[Vermont]], and [[Wyoming]] have fewer residents.<ref name=\"PopEstUS\"/>\n\nAs of 2019, South Dakota had an estimated population of 884,659, an increase of 70,479, or 8.66%, since the year 2010.<ref name=SDQuickfacts>{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts (South Dakota)|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 22, 2008|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/46000.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916025512/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/46000.html|archive-date=September 16, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> 7.3% of South Dakota's population was reported as under 5, 24% under 18, and 14.3% were 65 or older.<ref name=SDQuickfacts/> Females made up approximately 50.2% of the population.<ref name=SDQuickfacts/> As of the 2000 census, South Dakota ranked fifth-lowest in the nation in population and population density.\n\nOf the people residing in South Dakota, 65.7% were born in South Dakota, 31.4% were born in another U.S. state, 0.6% were born in Puerto Rico, U.S. Island areas, or born abroad to American parent(s), and 2.3% were born in another country.<ref>[https://www.census.gov U.S. Census website\u2014Results<!--Bot generated title-->] </ref>\n\nThe [[center of population]] of South Dakota is in [[Buffalo County, South Dakota|Buffalo County]], in the unincorporated county seat of [[Gann Valley, South Dakota|Gann Valley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Population and Population Centers by State\u20142000 |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=August 18, 2007 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/cenpop/statecenters.txt |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011212170351/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/cenpop/statecenters.txt |archivedate=December 12, 2001 }}</ref>\n\n===Ethnicity===\n\nAccording to the 2010 Census, the racial composition of the population was:\n* 84.7% [[White American|White]] (83.8% [[non-Hispanic white]])\n* 8.8% [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian]] and Alaska Native\n* 1.2% [[African American]] or black\n* 0.9% [[Asian American]]\n* 0.1% from some other race\n* 1.8% of two or more races\n\nEthnically, 2.7% of South Dakota's population was of [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic]], Latino, or Spanish origin (they may be of any race).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n|+ '''South Dakota racial breakdown of population'''\n|-\n! Racial composition !! 1990<ref>[https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html Historical Census Statistics on Population Totals By Race, 1790 to 1990, and By Hispanic Origin, 1970 to 1990, For The United States, Regions, Divisions, and States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725044857/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0056/twps0056.html |date=July 25, 2008 }}</ref>!! 2000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://censusviewer.com/city/SD|title=Population of South Dakota: Census 2010 and 2000 Interactive Map, Demographics, Statistics, Quick Facts|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>!! 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census/decade.2010.html|title=2010 Census Data|publisher=|access-date=December 11, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[White American|White]] || 91.6% || 88.7% || 85.7%\n|-\n| [[Native Americans in the United States|Native]] || 7.3% || 8.2% || 8.8%\n|-\n| [[African American]] || 0.5% || 0.6% || 1.3%\n|-\n| [[Asian American|Asian]] || 0.4% || 0.6% || 0.9%\n|-\n| [[Native Hawaiian]] and <br />[[Pacific Islander|other Pacific Islander]] || \u2013 || \u2013 || 0.1%\n|-\n| [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|Other race]] || 0.2% || 0.5% || 0.9%\n|-\n| [[Multiracial American|Two or more races]] || \u2013 || 1.4% || 2.1%\n|}\n\nAs of 2011, 25.4% of South Dakota's population younger than age 1 were minorities, meaning they had at least one parent who was not non-Hispanic white.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/datacentral/index.ssf/2012/06/americas_under_age_1_populatio.html|title=Americans under age 1 now mostly minorities, but not in Ohio: Statistical Snapshot|last=Exner|first=Rich|date=June 3, 2012|work=[[The Plain Dealer]]|access-date=August 18, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714084214/http://www.cleveland.com/datacentral/index.ssf/2012/06/americas_under_age_1_populatio.html|archive-date=July 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2000, the five largest ancestry groups in South Dakota are [[German-American|German]] (40.7%), [[Norwegian-American|Norwegian]] (15.3%), [[Irish American|Irish]] (10.4%), [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]] (8.3%), and [[English-American|English]] (7.1%).<ref name=CensusSocialStats>{{cite web | title = Quick Tables | publisher = United States Census Bureau | accessdate = August 29, 2008 | url = http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=n&_lang=en&qr_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U_DP2&ds_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U&geo_id=04000US46 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20200212042258/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/QTTable?_bm=n&_lang=en&qr_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U_DP2&ds_name=DEC_2000_SF3_U&geo_id=04000US46 | archive-date = February 12, 2020 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nGerman Americans are the largest ancestry group in most parts of the state, especially in East River (east of the Missouri River), although there are also large Scandinavian-descended populations in some counties. South Dakota has the nation's largest population of [[Hutterites]],<ref>{{cite web | title = Color them plain but successful | publisher = The Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis | accessdate = December 14, 2008 | url = https://www.minneapolisfed.org/publications_papers/pub_display.cfm?id=1409 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090116013816/http://www.minneapolisfed.org/publications_papers/pub_display.cfm?id=1409 | archive-date = January 16, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref> a communal [[Anabaptist]] group which emigrated in 1874 from Europe, primarily from German-speaking areas.\n[[File:National-atlas-indian-reservations-south-dakota.gif|thumb|left|upright=1.35|[[Indian reservation]]s in South Dakota]]\n\n[[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indians]], largely [[Lakota people|Lakota]], [[Sioux#Linguistics|Dakota]], and [[Nakota]] (Sioux), are predominant in several counties and constitute 20 per cent of the population in [[West River (South Dakota)|West River]]. The seven large Indian reservations in the state occupy an area much diminished from their former [[Great Sioux Reservation]] of West River, which the federal government had once allocated to the Sioux tribes. South Dakota has the third-highest proportion of Native Americans of any state, behind Alaska and [[New Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web | title = States Ranked by American Indian and Alaska Native Population, July&nbsp;1, 1999 | publisher = United States Census Bureau | accessdate = December 14, 2008 | url = https://www.census.gov/population/estimates/state/rank/aiea.txt | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081201024047/http://www.census.gov/population/estimates/state/rank/aiea.txt | archive-date = December 1, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nFive of the state's counties are wholly within the boundaries of sovereign [[Indian reservation]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Releases\u2014Uniquely South Dakota |publisher=South Dakota Department of Tourism |accessdate=August 22, 2008 |url=http://www.travelsd.com/Newsroom/pressreleases/uniquelysd.asp?id=356 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210034323/http://www.travelsd.com/newsroom/pressreleases/uniquelysd.asp?id=356 |archivedate=December 10, 2008 }}</ref> Because of the limitations of climate and land, and isolation from urban areas with more employment opportunities, living standards on many South Dakota reservations are often far below the national average; [[Ziebach County, South Dakota|Ziebach County]] ranked as the poorest county in the nation in 2009.<ref>Garrigan, Mary. \"Ziebach County still poorest in America\" [http://www.rapidcityjournal.com/news/article_eda45bae-040a-11e0-92aa-001cc4c03286.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510115722/http://www.rapidcityjournal.com/news/article_eda45bae-040a-11e0-92aa-001cc4c03286.html |date=May 10, 2011 }} ''The [[Rapid City Journal]]'', 10 December 2010. (accessed May 20, 2011)</ref> The unemployment rate in [[Fort Thompson, South Dakota|Fort Thompson]], on the [[Crow Creek Reservation]], is 70%, and 21% of households lack plumbing or basic kitchen appliances.<ref>[http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/200210/02_hetlandc_census-m/ Hetland, Cara. \"South Dakota has nation's poorest county\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809122011/http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/200210/02_hetlandc_census-m/ |date=August 9, 2018 }}, [[Minnesota Public Radio]]. October 1, 2002. (accessed December 19, 2008)</ref> A 1995 study by the U.S. Census Bureau found 58% of homes on the [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]] did not have a telephone.<ref>{{cite web | title = Transportation and Tourism Development at the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation | publisher = Federal Highway Administration | accessdate = December 19, 2008 | url = http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/economic_development/technical_and_analytical/pineridge.cfm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120615224754/http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/economic_development/technical_and_analytical/pineridge.cfm | archive-date = June 15, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> The reservations' isolation also inhibits their ability to generate revenue from gaming casinos, an avenue that has proved profitable for many tribes closer to urban centers.\n\n===Languages===\n\nIn 1995 the legislature passed a law to make English the \"common language\" of the state.<ref name=EnglishCommon/> Since 2019, ''\"the language of the [[Great Sioux Nation]], {{sic|comprised |hide=y|of}} three dialects, [[Sioux language|Dakota, Lakota, and Nakota\"]]'' is an official language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sdlegislature.gov/docs/legsession/2019/Amendments/amd126ca.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709163507/http://sdlegislature.gov/docs/legsession/2019/Amendments/amd126ca.htm |archive-date=July 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu.argusleader.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/22/south-dakota-recognizes-official-indigenous-language-governor-noem/3245113002/ |title=South Dakota recognizes official indigenous language |date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> As of the 2000 census, 1.90% of the population age{{nbsp}}5 or older speak German at home, while 1.51% speak [[Lakota language|Lakota]] or [[Dakota language|Dakota]], and 1.43% Spanish.<ref>{{cite web | title = Most Spoken Languages in South Dakota | publisher = mla.org | accessdate = August 18, 2007 | url = http://www.mla.org/map_data_results&state_id=46&mode=state_tops | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930182657/http://www.mla.org/map_data_results%26state_id%3D46%26mode%3Dstate_tops | archive-date = September 30, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> As of 2010, 93.46% (692,504) of South Dakota residents age{{nbsp}}5 and older spoke [[English language|English]] as their [[primary language]]. 6.54% of the population spoke a language other than English. 2.06% (15,292) of the population spoke Spanish, 1.39% (10,282) spoke [[Sioux language|Dakota]], and 1.37% (10,140) spoke German. Other languages spoken included [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]] (0.16%), [[Chinese language|Chinese]] (0.12%), and [[Russian language|Russian]] (0.10%).<ref>{{cite web|title=Most Spoken Languages in South Dakota In 2010 |publisher=[[Modern Language Association]] |accessdate=2013-12-14 |url=http://www.mla.org/cgi-shl/docstudio/docs.pl?map_data_results |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815140430/http://www.mla.org/cgi-shl/docstudio/docs.pl?map_data_results |archivedate=August 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Growth and rural flight===\n\nOver the last several decades, the population in many rural areas has declined in South Dakota, in common with other Great Plains states. The change has been characterized as \"[[rural flight]]\" as family farming has declined. Young people have moved to cities for other employment. This trend has continued in recent years, with 30 of South Dakota's counties losing population between the 1990 and the 2000 census.<ref name=ODriscoll>[https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/census/sd.htm O'Driscoll, Patrick. \"Sioux Falls powers South Dakota growth\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729023239/http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/census/sd.htm |date=July 29, 2010 }}, ''[[USA Today]]'', March 12, 2001. (accessed December 16, 2008)</ref> During that time, nine counties had a population loss of greater than 10%, with [[Harding County, South Dakota|Harding County]], in the northwest corner of the state, losing nearly 19% of its population.<ref name=ODriscoll/> Low birth rates and a lack of younger [[immigration]] has caused the median age of many of these counties to increase. In 24 counties, at least 20% of the population is over the age of 65,<ref>{{cite web|title=South Dakota state and county demographic profiles |publisher=South Dakota State University |accessdate=December 16, 2008 |url=http://agbionews.sdstate.edu/story.cfm?id=4420 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106004418/http://agbionews.sdstate.edu/story.cfm?id=4420 |archivedate=January 6, 2009 }}</ref> compared with a national rate of 12.8%.<ref name=SDQuickfacts/>\n\nThe effect of rural flight has not been spread evenly through South Dakota, however. Although most rural counties and small towns have lost population, the Sioux Falls area, the larger counties along [[Interstate 29 in South Dakota|Interstate 29]], the Black Hills, and many [[Indian reservations]] have all gained population.<ref name=ODriscoll/> As the reservations have exercised more sovereignty, some Sioux have returned to them from urban areas. [[Lincoln County, South Dakota|Lincoln County]] near Sioux Falls was the seventh fastest-growing county (by percentage) in the United States in 2010.<ref>{{cite web | title = Fastest Growing U.S. Counties | publisher = CNN | accessdate = March 15, 2016 | url = http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2010/real_estate/1006/gallery.fastest_growing_US_counties/7.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160317160749/http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2010/real_estate/1006/gallery.fastest_growing_US_counties/7.html | archive-date = March 17, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> The growth in these areas has compensated for losses in the rest of the state.<ref name=ODriscoll/> South Dakota's total population continues to increase steadily, albeit at a slower rate than the national average.<ref name=SDQuickfacts/>\n\n===Religion===\n\n[[File:East Side Lutheran Church Sioux Falls 2.JPG|thumb|East Side Lutheran Church, Sioux Falls]]\n\nThe largest denominations by number of adherents in 2010 were the Roman Catholic Church with 148,883 members; the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]] (ELCA) with 112,649 members; and the [[United Methodist Church]] (UMC) with 36,020 members.<ref name=\"www.thearda.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thearda.com/rcms2010/r/s/46/rcms2010_46_state_adh_2010.asp |title=The Association of Religion Data Archives &#124; State Membership Report |publisher=www.thearda.com |accessdate=December 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416200527/http://www.thearda.com/rcms2010/r/s/46/rcms2010_46_state_adh_2010.asp |archive-date=April 16, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (The ELCA and UMC are specific denominations within the broader terms 'Lutheran' and 'Methodist', respectively.)\nThe results of a 2001 survey, in which South Dakotans were asked to identify their religion, include:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gc.cuny.edu/faculty/research_briefs/aris/key_findings.htm |title=American Religious Identification Survey |website=Exhibit 15 |publisher=The Graduate Center, City University of New York |accessdate=April 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320221156/http://www.gc.cuny.edu/faculty/research_briefs/aris/key_findings.htm |archivedate=March 20, 2007 }}</ref>\n* Christian (86%)\n** Protestant (54%)\n*** [[Lutheran]] (27%)\n*** [[Methodist]] (13%)\n*** [[Baptist]] (4%)\n*** [[Presbyterian]] (4%)\n*** Other Protestant (6%)\n** Roman Catholic (25%)\n** [[non-denominational|Non-denominational Christian]] (7%)\n* Not religious (8%)\n* Other religions (3%)\n* Refused to answer (2%)\n\n==Economy==\n\n{{See also|South Dakota locations by per capita income}}\n[[File:B-1B Take Off.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|A [[B-1B Lancer]] lifts off from [[Ellsworth Air Force Base]], one of South Dakota's largest employers]]\n\nThe current-dollar [[gross state product]] of South Dakota was $39.8&nbsp;billion as of 2010, the fifth-smallest total state output in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web | title = Table 3. Current-Dollar GDP by State, 2007\u20132010 | publisher = [[Bureau of Economic Analysis]] | accessdate = August 25, 2011 | url = https://www.bea.gov/newsreleases/regional/gdp_state/2011/pdf/gsp0611.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110719041705/http://www.bea.gov/newsreleases/regional/gdp_state/2011/pdf/gsp0611.pdf | archive-date = July 19, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The [[Per capita personal income in the United States|per capita personal income]] was $38,865 in 2010, ranked 25th in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web | title = SA1-3 Per capita income (dollars) | publisher = [[Bureau of Economic Analysis]] | accessdate = August 25, 2011 | url = https://www.bea.gov/regional/spi/drill.cfm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150923192707/http://www.bea.gov/regional/spi/drill.cfm | archive-date = September 23, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and 12.5% of the population was below the poverty line in 2008.<ref>{{cite web | title = Persons Below Poverty Level, 2008 | publisher = [[United States Census Bureau]] | accessdate = August 25, 2011 | url = https://www.census.gov/compendia/statab/2011/ranks/rank34.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110817031706/http://www.census.gov/compendia/statab/2011/ranks/rank34.html | archive-date = August 17, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\nCNBC's list of \"Top States for Business for 2010\" has recognized South Dakota as the seventh best state in the nation.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/37516043/ \"America's Top States for Business 2010\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111226183123/http://www.cnbc.com/id/37516043 |date=December 26, 2011 }} CNBC Special Report (2010): 1. Web. May 9, 2011.</ref> In July 2011, the state's unemployment rate was 4.7%.<ref>{{cite web | title = Local Area Unemployment Statistics | publisher = [[Bureau of Labor Statistics]] | accessdate = May 9, 2011 | url = http://www.bls.gov/lau/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180725005015/https://www.bls.gov/lau/ | archive-date = July 25, 2018 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[service industry]] is the largest economic contributor in South Dakota. This sector includes the retail, finance, and health care industries. [[Citibank]], which was the largest bank holding company in the United States at one time, established national banking operations in South Dakota in 1981 to take advantage of favorable banking regulations.<ref name=Citibank/> Government spending is another important segment of the state's economy, providing over ten percent of the gross state product. [[Ellsworth Air Force Base]], near Rapid City, is the second-largest single employer in the state.<ref>Reha, Bob. ''South Dakota's Ellsworth AFB to stay open''. [http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/2005/08/26_rehab_ellsworthopen/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070127161020/http://news.minnesota.publicradio.org/features/2005/08/26_rehab_ellsworthopen/ |date=January 27, 2007 }} [[Minnesota Public Radio]]. August 26, 2005. (accessed September 8, 2007)</ref>\n[[File:SDethnl1.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.15|[[Ethanol]] plant in [[Turner County, South Dakota|Turner County]]]]\n\nAgriculture has historically been a key component of the South Dakota economy. Although other industries have expanded rapidly in recent decades, agricultural production is still very important to the state's economy, especially in rural areas. The five most valuable agricultural products in South Dakota are cattle, [[maize|corn (maize)]], [[soybeans]], [[wheat]], and [[pig|hogs]].<ref>{{cite web | title = State Fact Sheets: South Dakota | publisher = [[United States Department of Agriculture]] | accessdate = June 25, 2009 | url = http://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/state-fact-sheets/state-data.aspx?StateFIPS=46&StateName=South%20Dakota#.U8LWu_ldUeo | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120729083935/http://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/state-fact-sheets/state-data.aspx?StateFIPS=46&StateName=South%20Dakota#.U8LWu_ldUeo | archive-date = July 29, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> Agriculture-related industries such as [[meat packing]] and [[ethanol]] production also have a considerable economic impact on the state. South Dakota is the sixth leading ethanol-producing state in the nation.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ethanol Production By State | publisher = Nebraska Energy Office | accessdate = June 30, 2007 | url = http://www.neo.ne.gov/statshtml/121.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070415050748/http://www.neo.ne.gov/statshtml/121.htm | archive-date = April 15, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nAnother important sector in South Dakota's economy is tourism. Many travel to view the attractions of the state, particularly those in the [[Black Hills]] region, such as historic [[Deadwood, South Dakota|Deadwood]], [[Mount Rushmore]], and the nearby state and national parks. One of the largest tourist events in the state is the annual [[Sturgis Motorcycle Rally]]. The five-day event drew over 739,000 attendees in 2015; significant considering the state has a total population of 850,000.<ref name=Sturgisrally>{{cite web | url = http://www.argusleader.com/story/news/2014/08/04/sturgis-rally-attendance-expected-top-last-year/13563401/ | title = Sturgis rally attendance expected to top last year | format = | website = | publisher = [[Argus Leader]] | date = August 4, 2014 | accessdate = August 24, 2014 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20140824145325/http://www.argusleader.com/story/news/2014/08/04/sturgis-rally-attendance-expected-top-last-year/13563401/ | archive-date = August 24, 2014 | url-status = live }}</ref> In 2006, tourism provided an estimated 33,000 jobs in the state and contributed over two billion dollars to the economy of South Dakota.<ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota Tourism Statistics | publisher = South Dakota Department of Tourism | accessdate = April 6, 2007 | url = http://sdvisit.com/tools/facts/index.asp | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110216210634/http://www.sdvisit.com/tools/facts/index.asp | archive-date = February 16, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\n{{Main|Transportation in South Dakota}}\n{{See also|List of South Dakota railroads|List of South Dakota numbered highways}}\n[[File:Beaver Creek Bridge in Wind Cave National Park.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Beaver Creek Bridge in [[Wind Cave National Park]]]]\n\nSouth Dakota has {{convert|83,609|mi|km}} of highways, roads, and streets, along with {{convert|679|mi|km}} of [[interstate highways]].<ref>{{cite web | title = General Information/Key Facts | publisher = South Dakota Department of Transportation | accessdate = September 3, 2007 | url = http://www.sddot.com/geninfo_facts.asp | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120412194435/http://sddot.com/geninfo_facts.asp | archive-date = April 12, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> Two major interstates pass through South Dakota: [[Interstate 90 in South Dakota|Interstate 90]], which runs east and west through the southern half of the state; and [[Interstate 29 in South Dakota|Interstate 29]], running north and south in the eastern portion of the state. The I-29 corridor features generally higher rates of population and economic growth than areas in eastern South Dakota further from the interstate.<ref name=ODriscoll/>\n\nAlso in the state are the shorter Interstates [[Interstate 190 (South Dakota)|190]], a [[spur route|spur]] into central Rapid City, and [[Interstate 229 (South Dakota)|229]], a [[loop route|loop]] around southern and eastern Sioux Falls. Several major [[United States Numbered Highways|U.S. highways]] pass through the state. U.S. routes [[U.S. Route 12|12]], [[U.S. Route 14|14]], [[U.S. Route 16|16]], [[U.S. Route 18|18]] and [[U.S. Route 212|212]] travel east and west, while U.S. routes [[U.S. Route 81|81]], [[U.S. Route 83|83]], [[U.S. Route 85|85]] and [[U.S. Route 281|281]] run north and south. South Dakota and [[Montana]] are the only states sharing a land border which is not traversed by a paved road.\n\nSouth Dakota contains two [[National Scenic Byway]]s. The [[Peter Norbeck Scenic Byway|Peter Norbeck National Scenic Byway]] is in the Black Hills, while the Native American Scenic Byway runs along the Missouri River in the north-central part of the state.<ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota | publisher = [[Federal Highway Administration]] | accessdate = February 10, 2016 | url = http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways/states/SD | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160125193013/http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways/states/SD | archive-date = January 25, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> Other scenic byways include the Badlands Loop Scenic Byway, the Spearfish Canyon Scenic Byway, and the Wildlife Loop Road Scenic Byway.\n\nRailroads have played an important role in South Dakota transportation since the mid-19th century. Some {{convert|4420|mi|km}} of railroad track were built in South Dakota during the late 19th century and early 20th century,<ref>Thompson (ed.) p. 489.</ref> but only {{convert|1839|mi|km}} are active.<ref name=\"Railplan\">{{cite web | title = South Dakota State Rail Plan | publisher = South Dakota Department of Transportation | accessdate = February 10, 2016 | url = http://www.sddot.com/transportation/railroads/railplan/DR2_Vol1_SDDOT_StateRlPln.pdf | page = 9 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161001200635/http://sddot.com/transportation/railroads/railplan/DR2_Vol1_SDDOT_StateRlPln.pdf | archive-date = October 1, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> [[BNSF Railway]] is the largest railroad in South Dakota; the [[Rapid City, Pierre and Eastern Railroad]] (formerly the [[Dakota, Minnesota and Eastern]]) is the state's other major carrier.<ref name=Railplan/> Other state carriers include [[Dakota Southern Railway]], [[Dakota and Iowa Railroad]], [[Ellis and Eastern Company|Ellis and Eastern Railroad]], [[Sunflour Railroad]], [[Canadian Pacific Railway]], and the [[Sisseton Milbank Railroad]]. Rail transportation in the state is mostly freight, but there are two passenger heritage railroads: the [[Black Hills Central Railroad|Black Hills Central]] and the [[Prairie Village, Herman and Milwaukee Railroad|Prairie Village, Herman, and Milwaukee]]. However, South Dakota is one of the two [[Geographic contiguity|contiguous]] states that lack [[Amtrak]] service. (South Dakota is the only contiguous state that ''never had'' Amtrak\u2014[[Wyoming]] used to be served by the [[San Francisco Zephyr]] and the [[Pioneer (Amtrak)|Pioneer]].)<ref>{{cite web | title = Planning a Trip | publisher = frommers.com | accessdate = September 3, 2007 | url = http://www.frommers.com/destinations/southdakota/3738010002.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926215949/http://www.frommers.com/destinations/southdakota/3738010002.html | archive-date = September 26, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nSouth Dakota's largest commercial airports in terms of passenger traffic are the [[Sioux Falls Regional Airport]] and [[Rapid City Regional Airport]]. [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Frontier Airlines]], and [[Allegiant Airlines]], as well as commuter airlines using the brand affiliation with major airlines serve the two largest airports. Several other cities in the state also have commercial air service: [[Aberdeen Regional Airport]], [[Pierre Regional Airport]], and [[Watertown Regional Airport]], some of which is subsidized by the [[Essential Air Service]] program.<ref>{{cite web | title = What is Essential Air Service? | publisher = United States Department of Transportation | accessdate = December 13, 2008 | url = http://ntl.bts.gov/lib/1000/1500/1548/eas.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081217015828/http://ntl.bts.gov/lib/1000/1500/1548/eas.pdf | archive-date = December 17, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\n\n{{Main|Government of South Dakota}}\n[[File:SD Capitol.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|The [[South Dakota State Capitol]] in [[Pierre, South Dakota|Pierre]]]]\n\n===Government===\n\n{{See also|Governor of South Dakota|South Dakota Legislature|South Dakota Supreme Court}}\n\nLike other U.S. states, the structure of the government of South Dakota follows the same [[separation of powers]] as the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]], with executive, [[Legislature|legislative]], and [[Judiciary|judicial]] branches. The structure of the state government is laid out in the [[Constitution of South Dakota]], the highest law in the state. The constitution may be amended by a majority vote of both houses of the legislature, or by voter initiative.<ref>{{cite web | title = Article XXIII, Section 1, Constitution of South Dakota | publisher = South Dakota Legislature | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-23-1 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151207170852/http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-23-1 | archive-date = December 7, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Governor of South Dakota]] occupies the executive branch of the state government.<ref>{{cite web | title = Article IV, Section 1, Constitution of South Dakota | publisher = South Dakota Legislature | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-1 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151207170522/http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-1 | archive-date = December 7, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The current governor is [[Kristi Noem]], a Republican. The state constitution gives the governor the power to sign into law or veto bills passed by the state legislature, to serve as commander-in-chief of the [[South Dakota National Guard]], to appoint a cabinet, and to commute criminal sentences or to pardon those convicted of crimes.<ref>{{cite web | title = Article IV, Section 3, Constitution of South Dakota | publisher = South Dakota Legislature | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-3 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151207170524/http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-3 | archive-date = December 7, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Article IV, Section 4, Constitution of South Dakota | publisher = South Dakota Legislature | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-4 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151207170525/http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-4 | archive-date = December 7, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The governor serves for a four-year term, and may not serve more than two consecutive terms.<ref>{{cite web | title = Article IV, Section 2, Constitution of South Dakota | publisher = South Dakota Legislature | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-2 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151207170523/http://legis.sd.gov/Statutes/Constitution/DisplayStatute.aspx?Type=Statute&Statute=0N-4-2 | archive-date = December 7, 2015 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[South Dakota Legislature|state legislature]] is made up of two bodies, the [[South Dakota State Senate|Senate]], which has 35 members, and the [[South Dakota House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], with 70 members. South Dakota is divided into 35 legislative districts,<ref name=SDLegislature>{{cite web | title = The South Dakota Legislature: An Overview | publisher = State of South Dakota | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/docs/studentspage/studentguide/Overview.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113514/http://legis.sd.gov/docs/studentspage/studentguide/Overview.pdf | archive-date = March 4, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> with voters electing two representatives and one senator per district.<ref name=SDLegislature/> The legislature meets for an annual session which begins on the second Tuesday in January and lasts for 30 days; it also meets if a special session is called by the governor.<ref name=SDLegislature/>\n\nThe judicial branch is made up of several levels. The [[South Dakota Supreme Court|state supreme court]], with four justices and a chief justice, is the highest court in the state.<ref name=SDcourts>{{cite web | title = UJS Structure | publisher = South Dakota Unified Judicial System | accessdate = December 3, 2015 | url = http://ujs.sd.gov/About_the_Courts/structure.aspx | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190320015626/http://ujs.sd.gov/About_the_Courts/structure.aspx | archive-date = March 20, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Below the supreme court are the circuit courts; 41 circuit judges serve in seven judicial circuits in the state.<ref name=SDcourts/> Below the circuit courts are the [[Limited jurisdiction|magistrate courts]], which deal with more minor criminal and civil actions.<ref name=SDcourts/>\n\n===State taxes===\n\nAs of 2005, South Dakota has the lowest per capita total state tax rate in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | title = States Ranked by Total State Taxes and Per Capita Amount: 2005 | publisher = U.S. Census Bureau | accessdate = April 4, 2007 | url = https://www.census.gov/govs/statetax/05staxrank.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070409064417/http://www.census.gov/govs/statetax/05staxrank.html | archivedate = April 9, 2007 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The state does not levy personal or corporate [[income tax]]es,<ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota | publisher = The [[Tax Foundation]] | accessdate = January 31, 2010 | url = http://www.taxfoundation.org/research/topic/58.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100415005420/http://www.taxfoundation.org/research/topic/58.html | archive-date = April 15, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> [[inheritance tax]]es,<ref>{{cite web | title = Inheritance/Estate Tax | publisher = South Dakota Department of Revenue & Regulation | accessdate = January 27, 2008 | url = http://www.state.sd.us/drr2/propspectax/inheritance.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080207123321/http://www.state.sd.us/drr2/propspectax/inheritance.htm | archive-date = February 7, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref> or taxes on [[personal property|intangible personal property]]. The state [[sales tax]] rate is 4.5 percent.<ref>{{cite web | title = 2016 State Sales and Use Tax Increase | publisher = South Dakota Department of Revenue | accessdate = December 4, 2016 | url = http://dor.sd.gov/Taxes/Business_Taxes/HB1182.aspx | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161203123205/http://dor.sd.gov/Taxes/Business_Taxes/HB1182.aspx | archive-date = December 3, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> Various localities have local levies so in some areas the rate is six percent. The state sales tax does not apply to sales to [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indians]] on [[Indian reservation]]s, but many reservations have a compact with the state. Businesses on the reservation collect the tax and the state refunds to the Indian Tribes the percentage of sales tax collections relating to the ratio of Indian population to total population in the county or area affected. [[Ad valorem tax|Ad valorem]] [[property tax]]es are local taxes and are a large source of funding for school systems, counties, municipalities and other local government units. The [[South Dakota Special Tax Division]] regulates some taxes including cigarette and alcohol-related taxes.<ref>{{cite web | last =South Dakota Department of Revenue & Regulation | title =Special Tax Information | url =http://www.state.sd.us/drr2/propspectax/index.htm | accessdate =March 18, 2008 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20080308025844/http://www.state.sd.us/drr2/propspectax/index.htm | archive-date =March 8, 2008 | url-status =live }}</ref>\n\n===Federal representation===\n\n{{See also|List of United States Senators from South Dakota|List of United States Representatives from South Dakota}}\n\nSouth Dakota is represented at the federal level by [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John Thune]], Senator [[Mike Rounds]], and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Dusty Johnson]]. All three are Republicans. South Dakota is one of seven states with only one seat in the U.S. House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web | title = Member Information | publisher = Office of the Clerk\u2014[[United States House of Representatives]] | accessdate = April 5, 2009 | url = http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/olm110.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090528120146/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/olm110.html | archive-date = May 28, 2009 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In [[United States presidential election]]s, South Dakota is allotted three of 538 votes in the [[Electoral College (United States)|Electoral College]].<ref>{{cite web | title = U.S. Electoral College\u20142008 Presidential Election | publisher = archives.gov | accessdate = December 15, 2008 | url = http://archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/2008/allocation.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081205183218/http://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/2008/allocation.html | archive-date = December 5, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref> As in all other states except [[Maine]] and neighboring [[Nebraska]], South Dakota's electoral votes are granted in a winner-take-all system.<ref>{{cite web | title = U.S. Electoral College\u2014Frequently Asked Questions | publisher = archives.gov | accessdate = December 15, 2008 | url = https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/faq.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081218002735/http://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/faq.html | archive-date = December 18, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\n\n{{See also|Political party strength in South Dakota}}\n[[File:South Dakota Congressional Delegation 114th Congress.jpg|thumb|right|[[United States congressional delegations from South Dakota|Congressional delegation]]: (from left) Senator [[Mike Rounds]], Senator [[John Thune]], and Representative [[Kristi Noem]].]]\n\nSouth Dakota politics are generally dominated by the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Since statehood, Republicans have carried the state's electoral votes in all but five presidential elections: [[1896 United States presidential election|1896]], [[1912 United States presidential election|1912]] (by [[Theodore Roosevelt]]'s [[Progressive Party (United States, 1912)|Progressive Party]]), [[1932 United States presidential election|1932]], [[1936 United States presidential election|1936]] and [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]]. (Not to mention [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[George McGovern]]\u2014a native South Dakotan\u2014who failed in [[1972 United States presidential election|1972]].) Only [[Alaska]] has been carried fewer times by a Democrat.<ref>{{cite dictionary | title = McGovern, George Stanley, (1922\u2013) | dictionary = Biographical Directory of the United States Congress | accessdate = October 5, 2007 | url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=m000452 | date = | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927002702/http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M000452 | archivedate = September 27, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Presidential General Election Graph Comparison\u2014South Dakota | website = uselectionatlas.org | accessdate = October 5, 2007 | url = http://www.uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/comparegraphs.php?year=2004&fips=46&f=0&off=0&elect=0 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071015072307/http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/comparegraphs.php?year=2004&fips=46&f=0&off=0&elect=0 | archive-date = October 15, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> Additionally, a Democrat has not won the governorship since 1974. As of 2016, Republicans hold a 15% voter registration advantage over Democrats<ref>{{cite web | title = Voter Registration Tracking | publisher = South Dakota Secretary of State | accessdate = February 3, 2016 | url = https://sdsos.gov/elections-voting/upcoming-elections/voter-registration-totals/voter-registration-comparison-table.aspx | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160207184727/https://sdsos.gov/elections-voting/upcoming-elections/voter-registration-totals/voter-registration-comparison-table.aspx | archive-date = February 7, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> and hold large majorities in both the state House<ref>{{cite web | title = Official Listing\u2014South Dakota Representatives\u20142016 | publisher = State of South Dakota | accessdate = February 3, 2016 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Legislators/Legislators/Roster.aspx?Body=H&CurrentSession=True | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160203202328/http://legis.sd.gov/Legislators/Legislators/Roster.aspx?Body=H&CurrentSession=True | archive-date = February 3, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and the state Senate.<ref>{{cite web | title = Official Listing\u2014South Dakota Senators\u20142016 | publisher = State of South Dakota | accessdate = February 3, 2016 | url = http://legis.sd.gov/Legislators/Legislators/Roster.aspx?Body=S&CurrentSession=True | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160203202331/http://legis.sd.gov/Legislators/Legislators/Roster.aspx?Body=S&CurrentSession=True | archive-date = February 3, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDespite the state's general Republican and conservative leanings, Democrats have found success in various statewide elections, most notably in those involving South Dakota's congressional representatives in [[Washington D.C.|Washington]]. American Indians have been becoming more active in state and county electoral politics. In the 2002 election, American Indian voting carried Tim Johnson as the Democratic candidate by a margin of 532 votes.<ref name=Florio>[http://www.denverpost.com/Stories/0,1413,36%257E53%257E1095196%257E,00.html Gwen Florio, \"Indians Show Political Clout; Natives Throng Polls in 'White' S.D. County\"], {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081116003953/http://www.denverpost.com/Stories/0%2C1413%2C36~53~1095196~%2C00.html |date=November 16, 2008 }} ''The Denver Post'', January 8, 2003, accessed June 8, 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Statistics of the Congressional Election of November 2, 2002 | publisher = Office of the Clerk\u2014U.S. House of Representatives | accessdate = June 9, 2011 | url = http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2002/2002Stat.htm#41 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070105011809/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/2002/2002Stat.htm#41 | archive-date = January 5, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> Until his electoral defeat in 2004, Senator [[Tom Daschle]] was the Senate [[minority leader]] (and briefly its [[majority leader]] during Democratic control of the Senate in 2001\u201302).<ref>{{cite news | title = Daschle Loses S.D. Senate Seat to Thune | publisher = Fox News | accessdate = April 10, 2007 | url = http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,137397,00.html | date = November 3, 2004 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070523071147/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,137397,00.html | archive-date = May 23, 2007 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, South Dakota voted for Republican nominee [[Donald Trump]] over Democratic nominee [[Hillary Clinton]] by a margin of 30%.<ref name=16election>{{cite web | url = http://www.argusleader.com/story/news/politics/2016/11/05/sd-election-results-president-congress-ballot-measures/93370222/ | title = Election Results:President, Congress, ballot measures | publisher = [[Argus Leader]] | accessdate = December 4, 2016}}</ref> In 2018, Republican congresswoman [[Kristi Noem]] defeated Democrat [[Billie Sutton]] in the gubernatorial election, and Republican [[Dusty Johnson]] defeated Democrat Tim Bjorkman for the state's at-large seat in the U.S. House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://electionresults.sd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?type=SWR&map=CTY | title = Statewide Races | publisher = South Dakota Secretary of State | accessdate = December 16, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190330070533/http://electionresults.sd.gov/resultsSW.aspx?type=SWR&map=CTY | archive-date = March 30, 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nContemporary political issues in South Dakota include the costs and benefits of the [[South Dakota Lottery|state lottery]],<ref>{{cite web | title = About SD Lottery\u2014History | publisher = [[South Dakota Lottery]] | accessdate = June 26, 2009 | url = http://lottery.sd.gov/about/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090710011936/http://lottery.sd.gov/about/ | archive-date = July 10, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref> South Dakota's relatively low rankings in education spending (particularly teacher pay\u2014recently the State Sales Tax was increased from 4% to 4.5% to finance an increase in teacher pay),<ref>{{cite news | title = Quality Counts 2000\u2014Who Should Teach? | newspaper = Education Week | accessdate = April 9, 2007 | url = http://counts.edweek.org/sreports/qc00/templates/state-policy.cfm?slug=sd-up.htm }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and recent legislative and electoral attempts to ban abortion in the state.<ref>{{Cite news | title = South Dakota Abortion Ban Rejected | work = USA Today | date = November 8, 2006 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/politicselections/vote2006/SD/2006-11-08-abortion-ban_x.htm | accessdate = December 14, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081211073549/http://www.usatoday.com/news/politicselections/vote2006/SD/2006-11-08-abortion-ban_x.htm | archive-date = December 11, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>Rovner, Julie. ''South Dakotans Again Consider An Abortion Ban'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20081028192051/http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=95942981] [[National Public Radio]]. October 27, 2008. (accessed August 13, 2009).</ref>\n\nA [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] bill passed in March 2019 requires that all public schools display \"[[In God We Trust]]\" in a prominent location.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://legiscan.com/SD/text/SB55/id/1945148|title=South Dakota SB55 {{!}} 2019 {{!}} Regular Session|website=LegiScan|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726190623/https://legiscan.com/SD/text/SB55/id/1945148|archive-date=July 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/07/south-dakota-law-public-schools-display-in-god-we-trust-motto.html|title=South Dakota Law Requires Every Public School to Display \"In God We Trust\" National Motto|last=Hannon|first=Elliot|date=2019-07-26|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726190622/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/07/south-dakota-law-public-schools-display-in-god-we-trust-motto.html|archive-date=July 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n{{Main|Culture of South Dakota}}\n{{See also|List of people from South Dakota}}\n[[File:Black Elk.jpg|thumb|Nicholas [[Black Elk]] with his family, circa 1910]]\n\nSouth Dakota's culture reflects the state's American Indian, rural, Western, and European roots.<ref>{{Cite book|title=American nations : a history of the eleven rival regional cultures of North America|last=Woodard, Colin, 1968-|date=2012|publisher=Penguin Books|isbn=9781101544457|oclc=934597110}}</ref> A number of annual events celebrating the state's ethnic and historical heritage take place around the state, such as Days of '76 in [[Deadwood, South Dakota|Deadwood]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Days of '76 Celebration to include Saturday evening performance |publisher=Tri-State Livestock News |accessdate=January 29, 2010 |url=http://www.tsln.com/article/20090601/TSLN01/906019995/1023/NONE&parentprofile=1013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717110400/http://www.tsln.com/article/20090601/TSLN01/906019995/1023/NONE%26parentprofile%3D1013 |archivedate=July 17, 2011 }}</ref> Czech Days in [[Tabor, South Dakota|Tabor]],<ref>Thompson (ed.), p. 133.</ref> and the annual [[St. Patrick's Day]] and [[Cinco de Mayo]] festivities in Sioux Falls. The various tribes hold many annual [[pow wow]]s at their reservations throughout the state, to which non-Native Americans are sometimes invited.<ref>{{cite web|title=South Dakota Powwow Schedule |publisher=South Dakota Office of Tribal Government Relations |accessdate=January 29, 2010 |url=http://www.state.sd.us/oia/powwow.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204153350/http://www.state.sd.us/oia/powwow.asp |archivedate=February 4, 2010 }}</ref> [[Custer State Park]] holds an annual Buffalo Roundup, in which volunteers on horseback gather the park's herd of around 1,500 [[American bison|bison]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Buffalo Roundup and Arts Festival |publisher=South Dakota Department of Game, Fish and Parks |accessdate=January 29, 2010 |url=http://www.sdgfp.info/Parks/Regions/Custer/round.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204173345/http://www.sdgfp.info/Parks/Regions/Custer/round.htm |archivedate=February 4, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n[[Black Elk]] (Lakota) was a medicine man and [[heyokha]], whose life spanned the transition to reservations. His accounts of the 19th-century [[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]] and [[Ghost Dance]] movement, and his deep thoughts on personal visions and Native American religion, form the basis of the book ''[[Black Elk Speaks]]'', first published in 1932. (Among several editions, a premier annotated edition was published in 2008.)<ref name=\"ElkNeihardt2008\">{{cite book|author1=Black Elk|author2=John G. Neihardt|title=Black Elk Speaks: Being the Life Story of a Holy Man of the Oglala Sioux, the Premier Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7p9VqRLiKqcC&pg=PA149|date=16 October 2008|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1-4384-2540-5|pages=149\u2013|access-date=July 10, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170319061526/https://books.google.com/books?id=7p9VqRLiKqcC&pg=PA149|archive-date=March 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Writings of Black Elk | publisher = [[C-SPAN]] | website = [[American Writers: A Journey Through History]] | date = July 10, 2001 | accessdate = March 12, 2016 | url = http://www.c-span.org/video/?165060-1/writings-black-elk | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160312012706/http://www.c-span.org/video/?165060-1%2Fwritings-black-elk | archive-date = March 12, 2016 | url-status = live }}</ref> [[Paul Goble (writer and illustrator)|Paul Goble]], an award-winning children's book author and illustrator, has been based in the Black Hills since 1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paul Goble|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|url=http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/20771/Paul_Goble/index.aspx|accessdate=January 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206130901/http://harpercollins.com/authors/20771/Paul_Goble/index.aspx|archive-date=February 6, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Laura Ingalls Wilder]], whose semi-autobiographical books are based on her experiences as a child and young adult on the frontier, is one of South Dakota's best-known writers. She drew from her life growing up on a homestead near [[De Smet, South Dakota|De Smet]] as the basis for five of her novels: ''[[By the Shores of Silver Lake]]'', ''[[The Long Winter (novel)|The Long Winter]]'', ''[[Little Town on the Prairie]]'', ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'', and ''[[The First Four Years (novel)|The First Four Years]]''.<ref>{{cite web| title = Laura's History | publisher=Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Home and Museum | accessdate =December 19, 2008 | url = http://www.lauraingallswilderhome.com/history1.htm | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081201053959/http://www.lauraingallswilderhome.com/history1.htm<!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate =December 1, 2008}}</ref> These gained renewed popularity in the United States when ''Little House on the Prairie'' was adapted and produced as a television series in 1974. Wilder's daughter, [[Rose Wilder Lane]], who became a well-known writer in her own right, was born near De Smet in 1886.\n\nSouth Dakota has also produced several notable artists. [[Harvey Dunn]] grew up on a homestead near [[Manchester, South Dakota|Manchester]] in the late 19th century. While Dunn worked most of his career as a commercial illustrator, his most famous works showed various scenes of frontier life; he completed these near the end of his career.<ref>Hasselstrom, pp. 34\u201336.</ref> [[Oscar Howe]] ([[Crow]]) was born on the [[Crow Creek Indian Reservation]] and won fame for his watercolor paintings.<ref>Hasselstrom, pp. 215\u2013217.</ref> Howe was one of the first Native American painters to adopt techniques and style heavily influenced by the mid-20th century [[abstraction]] movement, rather than relying on traditional Native American styles. [[Terry Redlin]], originally from [[Watertown, South Dakota|Watertown]], is an accomplished painter of rural and wildlife scenes. Many of his works are on display at the [[Redlin Art Center]] in Watertown.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=410 | title = Terry Redlin | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 11, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110719104714/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=410 | archive-date = July 19, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Cities and towns==\n\n{{See also|List of cities in South Dakota|List of South Dakota counties}}\n[[File:Downtown Sioux Falls 61.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]], with a population of around 160,000, is the largest city in South Dakota.]]\n\n[[Sioux Falls, South Dakota|Sioux Falls]] is the largest city in South Dakota, with a 2010 population of 153,888,<ref name=2010CityPop>{{cite news | url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/census/profile/sd | title = South Dakota | newspaper = [[USA Today]] | accessdate = December 11, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121212105439/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/census/profile/SD | archive-date = December 12, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\nand a metropolitan area population of 238,122.<ref name=2009Metro>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/metro/files/2009/CBSA-EST2009-alldata.csv |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326160039/http://www.census.gov/popest/metro/files/2009/CBSA-EST2009-alldata.csv |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 26, 2010 |title=Metropolitan and micropolitan statistical area population and estimated components of change: April 1, 2000 to July 1, 2009 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 27, 2010 }}</ref>\nThe city, founded in 1856, is in the southeast corner of the state.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Sioux Falls |publisher=City of Sioux Falls |accessdate=October 6, 2008 |url=http://www.siouxfalls.org/Information/history/siouxfalls.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705075009/http://www.siouxfalls.org/Information/history/siouxfalls.aspx |archivedate=July 5, 2008 }}</ref> Retail, finance, and healthcare have assumed greater importance in Sioux Falls,<ref name=Thompson554>Thompson (ed.), p. 554.</ref> where the economy was originally centered on agri-business and quarrying.\n\n[[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]], with a 2010 population of 67,956,<ref name=2010CityPop/> and a metropolitan area population of 124,766,<ref name=2009Metro/> is the second-largest city in the state. It is on the eastern edge of the Black Hills, and was founded in 1876.<ref>Hasselstrom, p. 331.</ref> Rapid City's economy is largely based on tourism and defense spending,<ref name=Thompson554/> because of the proximity of many tourist attractions in the [[Black Hills]] and [[Ellsworth Air Force Base]].\n\nThe next eight largest cities in the state, in order of descending 2010 population, are [[Aberdeen, South Dakota|Aberdeen]] (26,091), [[Brookings, South Dakota|Brookings]] (22,056), [[Watertown, South Dakota|Watertown]] (21,482), [[Mitchell, South Dakota|Mitchell]] (15,254), [[Yankton, South Dakota|Yankton]] (14,454), [[Pierre, South Dakota|Pierre]] (13,646), [[Huron, South Dakota|Huron]] (12,592), and [[Vermillion, South Dakota|Vermillion]] (10,571).<ref name=2010CityPop/> Pierre is the state capital, and Brookings and Vermillion are the locations of the state's two largest universities ([[South Dakota State University]] and [[University of South Dakota]], respectively). With a population of about 14,000, Pierre is the second smallest state capital in the United States.<ref name=\"Jensen2012\">{{cite book|last=Jensen|first=Jamie|title=Road Trip USA: Cross-Country Adventures on America's Two-Lane Highways|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b9SuD5jagdwC&pg=PA194|date=December 1, 2012|publisher=Avalon Travel Publishing|isbn=978-1-61238-315-6|page=194|access-date=October 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509173434/https://books.google.com/books?id=b9SuD5jagdwC&pg=PA194|archive-date=May 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Of the ten largest cities in the state, only Rapid City is west of the [[Missouri River]].<ref name=2010CityPop/><ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota | publisher = National Atlas | accessdate = August 7, 2009 | url = http://www.nationalatlas.gov/printable/images/pdf/reference/pagegen_sd.pdf | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090826102340/http://nationalatlas.gov/printable/images/pdf/reference/pagegen_sd.pdf | archivedate = August 26, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n\n{{See also|List of newspapers in South Dakota|List of television stations in South Dakota|List of radio stations in South Dakota}}\n\nSouth Dakota's first newspaper, the ''Dakota Democrat'', began publishing in [[Yankton, South Dakota|Yankton]] in 1858.<ref>Hasselstrom, p. 202.</ref> Today, the state's largest newspaper is the Sioux Falls ''[[Argus Leader]]'', with a Sunday circulation of 63,701 and a weekday circulation of 44,334.<ref name=newspapercirc>{{cite web | url = http://abcas3.accessabc.com/ecirc/newsform.asp | title = US Newspaper\u2014Search Results (South Dakota) | publisher = Audit Bureau of Circulation | accessdate = December 13, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101001095406/http://abcas3.accessabc.com/ecirc/newsform.asp | archive-date = October 1, 2010 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The ''[[Rapid City Journal]]'', with a Sunday circulation of 32,638 and a weekday circulation of 27,827, is South Dakota's second largest newspaper.<ref name=newspapercirc/> The next four largest newspapers in the state are the [[Aberdeen, South Dakota|Aberdeen]] ''[[American News]]'', the ''[[Watertown Public Opinion]]'', the ''[[Huron Plainsman]]'', and the ''[[Brookings Register]]''.<ref name=newspapercirc/> In 1981, [[Tim Giago]] founded the ''Lakota Times'' as a newspaper for the local American Indian community on the [[Pine Ridge Indian Reservation]]. The newspaper, now published in New York and known as ''[[Indian Country Today]]'', is available in every state in the country.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=164 | title = Tim Giago | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 11, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930093145/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=164 | archive-date = September 30, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The ''[[Sioux City Journal]]'' also covers parts of South Dakota.\n\nThere are nine television stations broadcasting in South Dakota;<ref>{{cite web| year = 2007| url = http://www.globalcomputing.com/GetTV_Map1.cfm?PageNum_q_GetTV_Map=1&stateid=SD| title = U.S. Television Stations in South Dakota| publisher = Global Computing| accessdate = December 13, 2008| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711101343/http://www.globalcomputing.com/GetTV_Map1.cfm?PageNum_q_GetTV_Map=1&stateid=SD| archivedate = July 11, 2011| df = mdy-all}}</ref> [[South Dakota Public Television]] broadcasts from a number of locations around the state, while the other stations broadcast from Sioux Falls or Rapid City. The two largest television [[media market]]s in South Dakota are Sioux Falls-Mitchell, with a viewership of 246,020, and Rapid City, with a viewership of 91,070.<ref name=Nielson>{{cite web|date=2005\u20132006|url=http://www.nielsenmedia.com/DMAs.html|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060517010320/http://www.nielsenmedia.com/DMAs.html|archivedate=17 May 2006|title=Nielson Media Research Local Universe Estimates (US)|publisher=Nielson Media|accessdate=December 13, 2008}}</ref> The two markets rank as 114th and 177th largest in the United States, respectively.<ref name=Nielson/> The state's first television station, [[KELO-TV]], began airing in Sioux Falls in 1953. Among KELO's early programs was ''[[Captain 11]]'', an afternoon children's program. ''Captain 11'' ran from 1955 until 1996, making it the nation's longest continuously running children's television program.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://keloland.com/NewsDetail6162.cfm?Id=95595 | title = Dave Dedrick: 1928\u20132010 | publisher = [[KELO-TV]] | accessdate = January 23, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100126082805/http://www.keloland.com/NewsDetail6162.cfm?Id=95595 | archivedate = January 26, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA number of South Dakotans are famous for their work in television and publishing. Former [[NBC Nightly News]] anchor and author [[Tom Brokaw]] is from [[Webster, South Dakota|Webster]] and Yankton,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=58 | title = Tom Brokaw | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 11, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930093137/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=58 | archive-date = September 30, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' founder [[Al Neuharth]] was from [[Eureka, South Dakota|Eureka]] and [[Alpena, South Dakota|Alpena]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=368 | title = Allen Neuharth | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 26, 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930093210/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=368 | archive-date = September 30, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> gameshow host [[Bob Barker]] spent much of his childhood in [[Mission, South Dakota|Mission]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=24 | title = Robert (Bob) Barker | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 11, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930093128/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=24 | archive-date = September 30, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and entertainment news hosts [[Pat O'Brien (television)|Pat O'Brien]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=375 | title = Pat O'Brien | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 11, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930093116/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=375 | archive-date = September 30, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Mary Hart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=203 | title = Mary Hart | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = May 11, 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110930093049/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=203 | archive-date = September 30, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> are from Sioux Falls.\n\n==Education==\n\n{{See also|List of colleges and universities in South Dakota|List of high schools in South Dakota}}\n[[File:Coughlin Campanile 1.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Coughlin Campanile]], a landmark on the campus of [[South Dakota State University]] in [[Brookings, South Dakota|Brookings]]]]\n\nAs of 2006, South Dakota has a total primary and secondary school enrollment of 136,872, with 120,278 of these students being educated in the public school system.<ref>{{cite web| title = Student Demographics | publisher=South Dakota Department of Education | accessdate =November 26, 2007 | url = http://www.doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/studentdeomographics/k12enrollment.asp |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108120008/http://doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/studentdeomographics/k12enrollment.asp<!--Bot retrieved archive--> |archivedate = November 8, 2007}}</ref> There are 703 public schools<ref>{{cite web| title = School System By Type (2006\u201307) | publisher=South Dakota Department of Education | accessdate =November 26, 2007 | url = http://www.doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/schoolsandpersonnel/type.asp |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108115945/http://doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/schoolsandpersonnel/type.asp<!--Bot retrieved archive--> |archivedate = November 8, 2007}}</ref> in 168 school districts,<ref>{{cite web| title = Schools & Personnel | publisher=South Dakota Department of Education | accessdate =November 26, 2007 | url = http://www.doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/schoolsandpersonnel/numberofSD.asp |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108115954/http://doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/schoolsandpersonnel/numberofSD.asp<!--Bot retrieved archive--> |archivedate = November 8, 2007}}</ref> giving South Dakota the highest number of schools per capita in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | title = Number of Schools (most recent) (per capita) | publisher = statemaster.com | accessdate = November 26, 2007 | url = http://www.statemaster.com/graph/edu_ele_sec_tot_num_of_sch_percap-total-number-schools-per-capita | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080420102845/http://www.statemaster.com/graph/edu_ele_sec_tot_num_of_sch_percap-total-number-schools-per-capita | archive-date = April 20, 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The current high school graduation rate is 89.9%,<ref>{{cite web| title = South Dakota Graduation Rate | publisher=South Dakota Department of Education | accessdate =November 26, 2007 | url = http://www.doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/studentachievement/Graduationrate.asp |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108120013/http://doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/studentachievement/Graduationrate.asp<!--Bot retrieved archive--> |archivedate = November 8, 2007}}</ref> and the average [[ACT (examination)|ACT]] score is 21.8, slightly above the national average of 21.1.<ref>{{cite web| title = ACT Average Composite Score South Dakota vs. National | publisher=South Dakota Department of Education | accessdate =November 26, 2007 | url = http://www.doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/studentachievement/ACT.asp |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071108120016/http://doe.sd.gov/publications/annualreport/2007/studentachievement/ACT.asp<!--Bot retrieved archive--> |archivedate = November 8, 2007}}</ref> 89.8% of the adult population has earned at least a high school diploma, and 25.8% has earned a [[bachelor's degree]] or higher.<ref name=\"SD QuickFacts\">{{cite web|title=South Dakota QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/46000.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=2013-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040911075056/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/46000.html|archive-date=September 11, 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref> South Dakota's 2008 average public school teacher salary of $36,674 was the lowest in the nation (national average was $52,308).<ref>{{cite web | title = Rankings and Estimates 2008 | publisher = National Education Association | accessdate = January 30, 2010 | url = http://www.nea.org/home/29402.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100211170141/http://www.nea.org/home/29402.htm | archive-date = February 11, 2010 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In 2007 South Dakota passed legislation modeled after Montana's Indian Education for All Act (1999), mandating education about Native American tribal history, culture, and heritage in all the schools, from pre-school through college, in an effort to increase knowledge and appreciation about Indian culture among all residents of the state, as well as to reinforce Indian students' understanding of their own cultures' contributions.<ref name=\"teach.indian\">{{cite web |url=http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2012/04/12/montana-schools-try-keep-indian-students-engaged-teaching-indian-culture-all-107543 |author=Jawort, Adrian |title=Montana Schools Try to Keep Indian Students Engaged by Teaching Indian Culture to All |website=Indian Country Today |date=April 12, 2012 |accessdate=June 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020091328/http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/2012/04/12/montana-schools-try-keep-indian-students-engaged-teaching-indian-culture-all-107543 |archive-date=October 20, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[South Dakota Board of Regents]], whose members are appointed by the governor, controls the six public universities in the state. [[South Dakota State University]] (SDSU), in [[Brookings, South Dakota|Brookings]], is the state's largest university, with an enrollment of 12,831.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sdbor.edu/mediapubs/documents/SP12Total30TablesCensus.pdf | title = 2012 School Enrollments (Page 1) | publisher = [[South Dakota Board of Regents]] | accessdate = August 24, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140114113847/http://sdbor.edu/mediapubs/documents/SP12Total30TablesCensus.pdf | archive-date = January 14, 2014 | url-status = live }}</ref> The [[University of South Dakota]] (USD), in [[Vermillion, South Dakota|Vermillion]], is the state's oldest university, and has South Dakota's only [[University of South Dakota School of Law|law school]] and [[University of South Dakota Sanford School of Medicine|medical schoo]]l.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.sdbor.edu/jobopps/locations/locations.cfm | title = Locations | publisher=[[South Dakota Board of Regents]] | accessdate =April 18, 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080713023555/http://www.sdbor.edu/jobopps/locations/locations.cfm |archivedate = July 13, 2008}}</ref> South Dakota also has several private universities, the largest of which is [[Augustana University]] in Sioux Falls.\n\n==Sports and recreation==\n===Organized sports===\n\nBecause of its low population, South Dakota does not host any major league professional sports franchises. The state has minor league and independent league teams, all of which play in Sioux Falls or Rapid City. Sioux Falls is home to four teams: the [[Sioux Falls Canaries]] (baseball), the [[Sioux Falls Skyforce]] (basketball), the [[Sioux Falls Stampede]] ([[Ice hockey|hockey]]), and the [[Sioux Falls Storm]] ([[indoor American football]]).<ref>{{cite web | title = About Augustana\u2014City of Sioux Falls | publisher = Augustana College | accessdate = December 21, 2008 | url = http://www.augie.edu/about/sioux-falls | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080918223802/http://www.augie.edu/about/sioux-falls | archive-date = September 18, 2008 | url-status = live }}</ref> The Canaries play in the [[American Association of Independent Professional Baseball|American Association]], and their home field is [[Sioux Falls Stadium]]. The Skyforce play in the [[NBA G League]], and are owned by the NBA's [[Miami Heat]]. They play at the [[Sanford Pentagon]]. The Stampede and Storm share the [[Denny Sanford Premier Center]]. The Stampede play in the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]], and the Storm play in the [[Indoor Football League|IFL]]. Rapid City has a hockey team named the [[Rapid City Rush]] that plays in the [[ECHL]]. The Rush began their inaugural season in 2008 at the [[Rushmore Plaza Civic Center]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Rapid City Rush Hockey | publisher = Rapid City Visitors & Convention Bureau | accessdate = December 21, 2008 | url = http://vacations.visitrapidcity.inntopia.travel/aspnet/2.0/packageselect07.aspx?salesid=650555&packageid=3338&returnxml=0 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120604113120/http://vacations.visitrapidcity.inntopia.travel/aspnet/2.0/packageselect07.aspx?salesid=650555&packageid=3338&returnxml=0 | url-status = dead | archive-date = June 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nUniversities in South Dakota host a variety of sports programs. For many years, South Dakota was one of the only states in the country without an [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division I|Division{{nbsp}}I]] football or basketball team. However, several years ago SDSU decided to move their teams from [[NCAA Division II|Division{{nbsp}}II]] to Division{{nbsp}}I,<ref>{{cite web | title = SDSU approved for Division I membership | publisher = South Dakota State University | accessdate = December 21, 2008 | url = http://www.gojacks.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=15000&ATCLID=1498295&SPID=7147&SPSID=64578 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711105345/http://www.gojacks.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=15000&ATCLID=1498295&SPID=7147&SPSID=64578 | archive-date = July 11, 2011 | url-status = live }}</ref> a move followed by the [[University of South Dakota]].<ref>{{cite web | title = South Dakota leaves North Central Conference for D-I | publisher = ESPN | accessdate = December 21, 2008 | url = http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/news/story?id=2680524 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121019002422/http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/news/story?id=2680524 | archive-date = October 19, 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> Other universities in the state compete at the NCAA's Division II or III levels, or in the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]].\n\nFamous South Dakota athletes include [[Billy Mills]], [[Mike Miller (basketball player)|Mike Miller]], [[Mark Ellis (baseball)|Mark Ellis]], [[Becky Hammon]], [[Brock Lesnar]], [[Chad Greenway]], and [[Adam Vinatieri]]. Mills is from the town of [[Pine Ridge, South Dakota|Pine Ridge]] and competed at the [[1964 Summer Olympic Games]] in Tokyo, becoming the only American to win a gold medal in the 10,000-meter event.<ref>{{cite web | title = Billy Mills | publisher = South Dakota Hall of Fame | accessdate = March 15, 2016 | url = http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=349&first=&last=&catid=4&home_town=&date_inducted= | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161220105849/http://www.sdhalloffame.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=36&Itemid=78&iid=349&first=&last=&catid=4&home_town=&date_inducted= | archive-date = December 20, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Miller, of [[Mitchell, South Dakota|Mitchell]], is a two-time [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] champion who played college basketball at the University of Florida, leading them to the 2000 NCAA Championship game his sophomore year, and won the 2001 NBA rookie of the year award. Ellis, of Rapid City, played for the University of Florida and four [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] teams before retiring in 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title = Oakland Athletics\u2014Mark Ellis | publisher = [[ESPN]] | accessdate = January 29, 2010 | url = http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/players/profile?playerId=5086 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100412054943/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/players/profile?playerId=5086 | archive-date = April 12, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Mark Ellis retires from baseball at age 37 | publisher = NBC Sports | date = February 25, 2015 | accessdate = March 29, 2015 | url = http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/02/25/mark-ellis-retires-from-baseball-at-age-37/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150328064624/http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/02/25/mark-ellis-retires-from-baseball-at-age-37/ | archive-date = March 28, 2015 | url-status = live }}</ref> Hammon, of [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]], played for the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]'s [[New York Liberty]] and [[San Antonio Silver Stars]] before becoming an assistant coach for the NBA's [[San Antonio Spurs]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news | title = Profile\u2014Becky Hammon | work = [[Yahoo! Sports]] | accessdate = January 29, 2010 | url = https://sports.yahoo.com/wnba/players/289 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090804085447/http://sports.yahoo.com/wnba/players/289 | archive-date = August 4, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Becky Hammon Hired to Spurs' Staff | publisher = ESPN | accessdate = March 29, 2015 | url = http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11312366/becky-hammon-hired-san-antonio-spurs | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150407013912/http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11312366/becky-hammon-hired-san-antonio-spurs | archive-date = April 7, 2015 | url-status = live }}</ref> Lesnar, of [[Webster, South Dakota|Webster]], is a former heavy-weight champion in the UFC and WWE. Vinatieri is an [[National Football League|NFL]] [[placekicker]] who grew up in [[Rapid City, South Dakota|Rapid City]] and attended SDSU.<ref>{{cite news | title = New exhibit details Rapid City native Adam Vinatieri's kick | newspaper = [[Rapid City Journal]] | accessdate = March 19, 2016 | url = http://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/top-stories/new-exhibit-details-rapid-city-native-adam-vinatieri-s-kick/article_c4587602-c6ee-5b4e-bfb5-4ae958802016.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170725094023/http://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/top-stories/new-exhibit-details-rapid-city-native-adam-vinatieri-s-kick/article_c4587602-c6ee-5b4e-bfb5-4ae958802016.html | archive-date = July 25, 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n===Recreation===\n\n[[File:Mickelson Trail Tunnel.jpg|thumb|right|A tunnel along the [[George S. Mickelson Trail]] in the [[Black Hills]]]]\n\nFishing and hunting are popular outdoor activities in South Dakota. Fishing contributes over $224&nbsp;million to South Dakota's economy, and hunting contributes over $303&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web | title = Economic Impact | publisher = South Dakota Department of Game, Fish, and Parks | accessdate = March 12, 2016 | url = http://gfp.sd.gov/agency/information/economic-impact.aspx | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160311212616/http://www.gfp.sd.gov/agency/information/economic-impact.aspx | archive-date = March 11, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> In 2007, over 275,000 hunting licences and 175,000 fishing licences were sold in the state; around half of the hunting licences and over two-thirds of the fishing licences were purchased by South Dakotans.<ref>{{cite web | title = How many people hunt and fish in South Dakota? | publisher = South Dakota Department of Game, Fish, and Parks | accessdate = December 21, 2008 | url = http://www.sdgfp.info/Wildlife/Economics/Howmanyhuntandfish.htm | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081210033903/http://www.sdgfp.info/Wildlife/Economics/Howmanyhuntandfish.htm | archivedate = December 10, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Popular species of game include [[Common pheasant|pheasants]], [[White tailed deer|white-tailed deer]], [[mule deer]], and [[turkey (bird)|turkeys]], as well as waterfowl such as [[Canada goose|Canada geese]], [[snow geese]], and [[mallards]]. Targets of anglers include [[walleye]] in the eastern glacial lakes and Missouri River reservoirs,<ref>{{cite web | title = Fishing in South Dakota (Northeastern) | publisher = South Dakota Office of Tourism | accessdate = January 29, 2010 | url = http://www.travelsd.com/Outdoors/Fishing/Northeast-Region | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100204164423/http://www.travelsd.com/Outdoors/Fishing/Northeast-Region | archive-date = February 4, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref><ref name=MissouriFishing>{{cite web | title = Fishing in South Dakota (Central) | publisher = South Dakota Office of Tourism | accessdate = January 29, 2010 | url = http://www.travelsd.com/Outdoors/Fishing/Central-Region | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100204164730/http://www.travelsd.com/Outdoors/Fishing/Central-Region | archive-date = February 4, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> [[Chinook salmon]] in [[Lake Oahe]],<ref name=MissouriFishing/> and [[trout]] in the Black Hills.<ref>{{cite web | title = Fishing in South Dakota (Western) | publisher = South Dakota Office of Tourism | accessdate = January 29, 2010 | url = http://www.travelsd.com/Outdoors/Fishing/Western-Region | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100204164852/http://www.travelsd.com/Outdoors/Fishing/Western-Region | archive-date = February 4, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nOther sports, such as cycling and running, are also popular in the state. In 1991, the state opened the [[George S. Mickelson Trail]], a {{convert|109|mi|km|adj=on}} [[rail trail]] in the Black Hills.<ref>{{cite web | title = George S. Mickelson Trail Guide | publisher = South Dakota Department of Game, Fish and Parks | accessdate = January 29, 2010 | url = http://www.sdgfp.info/parks/regions/NorthernHills/MickelsonTrail/GSMTrailGuide.pdf | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100104185447/http://www.sdgfp.info/Parks/Regions/NorthernHills/MickelsonTrail/GSMTrailGuide.pdf | archivedate = January 4, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Besides being used by cyclists, the trail is also the site of a portion of the annual Mount Rushmore marathon; the marathon's entire course is at an elevation of over 4,000&nbsp;feet (1,200&nbsp;m).<ref>{{cite web | title = Course Info | publisher = Mount Rushmore Marathon | accessdate = December 21, 2008 | url = http://www.mtrushmoremarathon.com/new/Route/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051013062504/http://www.mtrushmoremarathon.com/new/Route/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = October 13, 2005 }}</ref> Other events in the state include the Tour de Kota, a {{convert|478|mi|km|adj=on}}, six-day cycling event that covers much of eastern and central South Dakota,<ref>{{cite web | title = Tour de Kota | publisher = Tour de Kota | accessdate = June 25, 2009 | url = http://www.tourdekota.com/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090105161516/http://tourdekota.com/ | archive-date = January 5, 2009 | url-status = live }}</ref> and the annual [[Sturgis Motorcycle Rally]], which draws hundreds of thousands of participants from around the United States.<ref name=Sturgisrally/>\n\n==State symbols==\n\n{{Main|List of South Dakota state symbols}}\n[[File:South Dakota quarter, reverse side, 2006.jpg|right|thumb|South Dakota's [[50 State quarters|quarter]] depicts [[Mt. Rushmore]], a [[Common pheasant|pheasant]], and wheat.]]\n\nSome of South Dakota's official state symbols include:<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.travelsouthdakota.com/about-south-dakota/south-dakota-facts | website = South Dakota Department of Tourism | title = South Dakota Facts | accessdate = May 12, 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150518072246/https://www.travelsouthdakota.com/about-south-dakota/south-dakota-facts | archive-date = May 18, 2015 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n:'''[[List of U.S. state birds|State bird]]:''' [[Common pheasant|Ring-necked pheasant]]\n:'''[[List of U.S. state flowers|State flower]]:''' [[Pulsatilla patens|American pasque flower]]\n:'''[[List of U.S. state trees|State tree]]:''' Black Hills [[spruce]]\n: '''[[List of U.S. state nicknames|State nicknames]]:''' [[Mount Rushmore]] State (official), [[Coyote]] state & [[Sunlight|Sunshine]] state (both unofficial)\n: '''[[List of U.S. state mottos|State motto]]:''' \"Under God, the people rule\"\n: '''State slogan:''' \"Great Faces. Great Places.\"\n:'''[[List of U.S. state minerals, rocks, stones and gemstones|State mineral]]:''' Rose [[quartz]]\n:'''[[List of U.S. state insects|State insect]]:''' [[Western honey bee|Honey bee]] (''Apis mellifera'')\n:'''[[List of U.S. state animals|State animal]]:''' [[Coyote]]\n:'''[[List of U.S. state fish|State fish]]:''' [[Walleye]]\n:'''[[List of U.S. state minerals, rocks, stones and gemstones|State gemstone]]:''' [[Fairburn, South Dakota|Fairburn]] [[agate]]\n:'''[[List of U.S. state songs|State song]]:''' \"[[Hail, South Dakota!]]\"\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n\n{{portal|United States}}\n* [[Outline of South Dakota]]\n* [[Index of South Dakota-related articles]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n* {{Cite book |title=Roadside History of South Dakota |last=Hasselstrom |first=Linda M. |year=1994 |publisher=[[Mountain Press Publishing Company]] |location=Missoula, MT |isbn=978-0-87842-262-3 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/roadsidehistoryo0000hass }}\n* {{Cite book|title=History of South Dakota |last=Schell |first=Herbert S. |year=2004 |publisher=[[South Dakota State Historical Society Press]] |location=Pierre, SD |isbn=978-0-9715171-3-4}}\n* {{Cite book|author=Thompson, Harry F. (ed.) |year=2009 |title=A New South Dakota History |edition=Second |publisher=Center for Western Studies\u2014[[Augustana College (South Dakota)|Augustana College]] |location=Sioux 